# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stellar-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] A **Hertzsprung–Russell diagram** (abbreviated as **H–R diagram**, **HR diagram** or **HRD**) is a scatter plot of stars showing the relationship between the stars' absolute magnitudes or luminosities and their stellar classifications or effective temperatures.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] It is also sometimes called a **color magnitude diagram**.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The diagram was created independently in 1911 by Ejnar Hertzsprung and by Henry Norris Russell in 1913, and represented a major step towards an understanding of stellar evolution.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] In the nineteenth century large-scale photographic spectroscopic surveys of stars were performed at Harvard College Observatory, producing spectral classifications for tens of thousands of stars, culminating ultimately in the Henry Draper Catalogue.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] In one segment of this work Antonia Maury included divisions of the stars by the width of their spectral lines.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Hertzsprung noted that stars described with narrow lines tended to have smaller proper motions than the others of the same spectral classification.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] He took this as an indication of greater luminosity for the narrow-line stars, and computed secular parallaxes for several groups of these, allowing him to estimate their absolute magnitude.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] In 1910 Hans Oswald Rosenberg published a diagram plotting the apparent magnitude of stars in the Pleiades cluster against the strengths of the calcium K line and two hydrogen Balmer lines.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] These spectral lines serve as a proxy for the temperature of the star, an early form of spectral classification.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The apparent magnitude of stars in the same cluster is equivalent to their absolute magnitude, so this early diagram was effectively a plot of luminosity against temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The same type of diagram is still used today as a means of showing the stars in clusters without having to initially know their distance and luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Hertzsprung had already been working with this type of diagram, but his first publications showing it were not until 1911.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This was also the form of the diagram using apparent magnitudes of a cluster of stars all at the same distance.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] There are several forms of the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, and the nomenclature is not very well defined.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] All forms share the same general layout: stars of greater luminosity are toward the top of the diagram, and stars with higher surface temperature are toward the left side of the diagram.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The original diagram displayed the spectral type of stars on the horizontal axis and the absolute visual magnitude on the vertical axis.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The spectral type is not a numerical quantity, but the sequence of spectral types is a monotonic series that reflects the stellar surface temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Modern observational versions of the chart replace spectral type by a color index (in diagrams made in the middle of the 20th Century, most often the B-V color) of the stars.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This type of diagram is what is often called an observational Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, or specifically a color–magnitude diagram (CMD), and it is often used by observers.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] In cases where the stars are known to be at identical distances such as within a star cluster, a color–magnitude diagram is often used to describe the stars of the cluster with a plot in which the vertical axis is the apparent magnitude of the stars.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] For cluster members, by assumption there is a single additive constant difference between their apparent and absolute magnitudes, called the distance modulus, for all of that cluster of stars.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Early studies of nearby open clusters (like the Hyades and Pleiades) by Hertzsprung and Rosenberg produced the first CMDs, a few years before Russell's influential synthesis of the diagram collecting data for all stars for which absolute magnitudes could be determined.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Another form of the diagram plots the effective surface temperature of the star on one axis and the luminosity of the star on the other, almost invariably in a log-log plot.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Theoretical calculations of stellar structure and the evolution of stars produce plots that match those from observations.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This type of diagram could be called *temperature-luminosity diagram*, but this term is hardly ever used; when the distinction is made, this form is called the *theoretical Hertzsprung–Russell diagram* instead.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] A peculiar characteristic of this form of the H–R diagram is that the temperatures are plotted from high temperature to low temperature, which aids in comparing this form of the H–R diagram with the observational form.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Although the two types of diagrams are similar, astronomers make a sharp distinction between the two.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The reason for this distinction is that the exact transformation from one to the other is not trivial.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] To go between effective temperature and color requires a color–temperature relation, and constructing that is difficult; it is known to be a function of stellar composition and can be affected by other factors like stellar rotation.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] When converting luminosity or absolute bolometric magnitude to apparent or absolute visual magnitude, one requires a bolometric correction, which may or may not come from the same source as the color–temperature relation.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] One also needs to know the distance to the observed objects (*i.e.*, the distance modulus) and the effects of interstellar obscuration, both in the color (reddening) and in the apparent magnitude (where the effect is called "extinction").
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Color distortion (including reddening) and extinction (obscuration) are also apparent in stars having significant circumstellar dust.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The ideal of direct comparison of theoretical predictions of stellar evolution to observations thus has additional uncertainties incurred in the conversions between theoretical quantities and observations.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Since around the 1970s there is also a third version of the Hertzsprung-Russell diagram that is referred to as either the spectroscopic H-R diagram or the Kiel diagram.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This presents the logarithm of the surface gravity (log g) on the y-axis, and the effective surface temperature (Teff) on the x-axis.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] In the spectroscopic H-R diagram, both axes are inverted such that both the surface gravity and the effective surface temperature are presented in descending order instead of ascending order.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The surface gravity and the effective surface temperature are often acquired spectroscopically, i.e. by measuring and analysing stellar spectra.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The data in the spectroscopic H-R diagram might not always have the exact same shape as is often seen in the CMD or the theoretical H-R diagram, but it shows similar features and shapes.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Measuring spectra with good resolution requires more resources than photometric measurements, which means that this kind of diagram cannot be created for all stars if they do not have good measured spectra.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Most of the stars occupy the region in the diagram along the line called the main sequence, with low-mass stars at the cooler and less luminous end of the sequence, and more massive stars towards the hotter and more luminous end.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] During the stage of their lives in which stars are found on the main sequence line, they are fusing hydrogen in their cores.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] A prominent group of cool stars is found at higher luminosities, and larger sizes, than main-sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] These are known as red giants and include: stars fusing hydrogen around an inert helium core, the red giant branch; stars fusing helium in their cores, the horizontal branch; and stars fusing helium and hydrogen in shells around a largely-inert core, the asymptotic giant branch.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The red giants are separated from the main sequence by the Hertzsprung gap, populated by subgiants and located in the region between A5 and G0 spectral type and between +1 and −3 absolute magnitudes.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Other groups of stars distinguished in the HR diagram are: supergiants, rare evolved massive stars prominent because of their high luminosity; white dwarfs, very common but with very low luminosities; and brown dwarfs, very cool and with very low luminosities.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] RR Lyrae variable stars are horizontal-branch stars in a section of the diagram called the instability strip.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Cepheid variables also fall on the instability strip, at higher luminosities.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The H-R diagram can be used by scientists to roughly measure how far away a star cluster or galaxy is from Earth.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This can be done by comparing the apparent magnitudes of the stars in the cluster to the absolute magnitudes of stars with known distances (or of model stars).
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The observed group is then shifted in the vertical direction, until the two main sequences overlap.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The difference in magnitude that was bridged in order to match the two groups is called the distance modulus and is a direct measure for the distance (ignoring extinction).
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This technique is known as main sequence fitting and is a type of spectroscopic parallax.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Not only the turn-off in the main sequence can be used, but also the tip of the red giant branch stars.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] ESA's Gaia mission showed several features in the diagram that were either not known or that were suspected to exist.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] It found a gap in the main sequence that appears for M-dwarfs and that is explained with the transition from a partly convective core to a fully convective core.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] For white dwarfs the diagram shows several features.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Two main concentrations appear in this diagram following the cooling sequence of white dwarfs that are explained with the atmospheric composition of white dwarfs, especially hydrogen versus helium dominated atmospheres of white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] A third concentration is explained with core crystallization of the white dwarfs interior.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This releases energy and delays the cooling of white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Contemplation of the diagram led astronomers to speculate that it might demonstrate stellar evolution, the main suggestion being that stars collapsed from red giants to dwarf stars, then moving down along the line of the main sequence in the course of their lifetimes.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Stars were thought therefore to radiate energy by converting gravitational energy into radiation through the Kelvin–Helmholtz mechanism.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This mechanism resulted in an age for the Sun of only tens of millions of years, creating a conflict over the age of the Solar System between astronomers, and biologists and geologists who had evidence that the Earth was far older than that.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This conflict was only resolved in the 1930s when nuclear fusion was identified as the source of stellar energy.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Following Russell's presentation of the diagram to a meeting of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1912, Arthur Eddington was inspired to use it as a basis for developing ideas on stellar physics.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] In 1926, in his book *The Internal Constitution of the Stars* he explained the physics of how stars fit on the diagram.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The paper anticipated the later discovery of nuclear fusion and correctly proposed that the star's source of power was the combination of hydrogen into helium, liberating enormous energy.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] This was a particularly remarkable intuitive leap, since at that time the source of a star's energy was still unknown, thermonuclear energy had not been proven to exist, and even that stars are largely composed of hydrogen (see metallicity), had not yet been discovered.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Eddington managed to sidestep this problem by concentrating on the thermodynamics of radiative transport of energy in stellar interiors.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] Eddington predicted that dwarf stars remain in an essentially static position on the main sequence for most of their lives.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] In the 1930s and 1940s, with an understanding of hydrogen fusion, came an evidence-backed theory of evolution to red giants following which were speculated cases of explosion and implosion of the remnants to white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/hertzsprung-russell-diagram] The term supernova nucleosynthesis is used to describe the creation of elements during the evolution and explosion of a pre-supernova star, a concept put forth by Fred Hoyle in 1954.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In astronomy, the **main sequence** is a classification of stars which appear on plots of stellar color versus brightness as a continuous and distinctive band.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Stars spend the majority of their lives on the main sequence, during which core hydrogen burning is dominant.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] These **main-sequence stars**, or sometimes interchangeably dwarf stars, are the most numerous true stars in the universe and include the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Color-magnitude plots are known as Hertzsprung–Russell diagrams after Ejnar Hertzsprung and Henry Norris Russell.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When a gaseous nebula undergoes sufficient gravitational collapse, the high pressure and temperature concentrated at the core will trigger the nuclear fusion of hydrogen into helium (see stars).
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The thermal energy from this process radiates out from the hot, dense core, generating a strong pressure gradient.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] It is this pressure gradient that counters the star's collapse under gravity, maintaining the star in a state of hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The star's position on the main sequence is determined primarily by the mass, but also by age and chemical composition.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] As a result, radiation is not the only method of energy transfer in stars.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Convection plays a role in the movement of energy, particularly in the cores of stars greater than 1.3 to 1.5 times the Sun's mass, again depending on age and chemical composition.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When discussing chemical composition, astronomers generally refer to the metallicity of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This is the abundance of heavier-than-helium elements present in the star.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For example, the fraction of the Sun by mass currently composed of hydrogen (denoted X) is 74.9%.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For helium (denoted Y) it is 23.8%, meaning the star's metallicity, or mass fraction of all other elements, is 1.3% (denoted Z).
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This is a typical range for similar-mass main sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In fact, a higher metallicity leads to a higher opacity whereby the energy production can remain concentrated in the core without being radiated or transferred away to the star's outer layers.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This hotter environment speeds up nuclear fusion and decreases the amount of time the star will spend on the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The main sequence is divided into upper and lower parts, based on the dominant process that a star uses to generate energy.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The Sun, along with main sequence stars below about 1.5 *M*☉, primarily fuse hydrogen atoms together in a series of stages to form helium, a sequence called the proton–proton chain.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Above this mass, in the upper main sequence, the nuclear fusion process mainly uses atoms of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen as intermediaries in the CNO cycle that produces helium from hydrogen atoms.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The proton-proton chain is still occurring, but it produces less energy than the CNO cycle.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Main-sequence stars where the CNO cycle is the dominant energy production process undergo convection in their core regions, which acts to stir up the newly created helium and maintain the proportion of fuel needed for fusion to occur.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Below this mass, stars have cores that are entirely radiative with convective zones near the surface.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] With decreasing stellar mass, the proportion of the star forming a convective envelope steadily increases.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The main-sequence stars below 0.4 *M*☉ undergo convection throughout their mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When core convection does not occur, a helium-rich core develops surrounded by an outer layer of hydrogen.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The more massive a star is, the shorter its lifespan on the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] After the hydrogen fuel at the core has been consumed, the star evolves away from the main sequence on the HR diagram, into a supergiant, red giant, or directly to a white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In the early part of the 20th century, information about the types and distances of stars became more readily available.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The spectra of stars were shown to have distinctive features, which allowed them to be categorized.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Annie Jump Cannon and Edward Charles Pickering at Harvard College Observatory developed a method of categorization that became known as the Harvard Classification Scheme, published in the *Harvard Annals* in 1901.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In Potsdam in 1906, the Danish astronomer Ejnar Hertzsprung noticed that the reddest stars—classified as K and M in the Harvard scheme—could be divided into two distinct groups.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] These stars are either much brighter than the Sun or much fainter.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] To distinguish these groups, he called them "giant" and "dwarf" stars.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The following year he began studying star clusters; large groupings of stars that are co-located at approximately the same distance.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For these stars, he published the first plots of color versus luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] These plots showed a prominent and continuous sequence of stars, which he named the Main Sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] At Princeton University, Henry Norris Russell was following a similar course of research.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] He was studying the relationship between the spectral classification of stars and their actual brightness as corrected for distance—their absolute magnitude.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For this purpose, he used a set of stars that had reliable parallaxes and many of which had been categorized at Harvard.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When he plotted the spectral types of these stars against their absolute magnitude, he found that dwarf stars followed a distinct relationship.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This allowed the real brightness of a dwarf star to be predicted with reasonable accuracy.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Of the red stars observed by Hertzsprung, the dwarf stars also followed the spectra-luminosity relationship discovered by Russell.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] However, giant stars are much brighter than dwarfs and so do not follow the same relationship.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Russell proposed that "giant stars must have low density or great surface brightness, and the reverse is true of dwarf stars".
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The same curve also showed that there were very few faint white stars.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In 1933, Bengt Strömgren introduced the term Hertzsprung–Russell diagram to denote a luminosity-spectral class diagram.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This name reflected the parallel development of this technique by both Hertzsprung and Russell earlier in the century.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] As evolutionary models of stars were developed during the 1930s, it was shown that, for stars with the same composition, the star's mass determines its luminosity and radius.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Conversely, when a star's chemical composition and its position on the main sequence are known, the star's mass and radius can be deduced.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This became known as the Vogt–Russell theorem; named after Heinrich Vogt and Henry Norris Russell.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] It was subsequently discovered that this relationship breaks down somewhat for stars of the non-uniform composition.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A refined scheme for stellar classification was published in 1943 by William Wilson Morgan and Philip Childs Keenan.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The MK classification assigned each star a spectral type—based on the Harvard classification—and a luminosity class.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The Harvard classification had been developed by assigning a different letter to each star based on the strength of the hydrogen spectral line before the relationship between spectra and temperature was known.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When ordered by temperature and when duplicate classes were removed, the spectral types of stars followed, in order of decreasing temperature with colors ranging from blue to red, the sequence O, B, A, F, G, K, and M.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] (A popular mnemonic for memorizing this sequence of stellar classes is "Oh Be A Fine Girl/Guy, Kiss Me".) The luminosity class ranged from I to V, in order of decreasing luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Stars of luminosity class V belonged to the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In April 2018, astronomers reported the detection of the most distant "ordinary" (i.e., main sequence) star, named Icarus (formally, MACS J1149 Lensed Star 1), at 9 billion light-years away from Earth.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When a protostar is formed from the collapse of a giant molecular cloud of gas and dust in the local interstellar medium, the initial composition is homogeneous throughout, consisting of approximately 70% hydrogen, 28% helium, and trace amounts of other elements, by mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The initial mass of the star depends on the local conditions within the cloud.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] (The mass distribution of newly formed stars is described empirically by the initial mass function.) During the initial collapse, this pre-main-sequence star generates thermal energy through the increase in pressure arising due to its gravitational contraction.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] During this phase, before hydrogen ignition, the star will spend a length of time contracting known as the Kelvin-Helmholtz, or thermal, timescale.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This timescale describes the length of time a star can last by radiating its internal kinetic energy.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Once sufficiently dense, stars begin converting hydrogen into helium and producing energy through an exothermic nuclear fusion process.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The nuclear timescale is useful to describe the length of time a star can last during this next phase.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When nuclear fusion of hydrogen becomes the dominant energy production process and the excess energy gained from gravitational contraction has been lost, the star lies along a curve on the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram (or HR diagram) called the standard main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Astronomers will sometimes refer to this stage as "zero-age main sequence", or ZAMS.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The ZAMS curve can be calculated using computer models of stellar properties at the point when stars begin hydrogen fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] From this point, the brightness and surface temperature of stars typically increase with age.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A star remains near its initial position on the main sequence until a significant amount of hydrogen in the core has been consumed, then begins to evolve into a more luminous star.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] (On the HR diagram, the evolving star moves up and to the right of the main sequence.) Thus the main sequence represents the primary hydrogen-burning stage of a star's lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] M-type (and, to a lesser extent, K-type) main-sequence stars are usually referred to as red dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The majority of stars on a typical HR diagram lie along the main-sequence curve.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This line is pronounced because both the spectral type and the luminosity depends only on a star's mass, at least to zeroth-order approximation, as long as it is fusing hydrogen at its core—and that is what almost all stars spend most of their "active" lives doing.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The temperature of a star determines its spectral type via its effect on the physical properties of plasma in its photosphere.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A star's energy emission as a function of wavelength is influenced by both its temperature and composition.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A key indicator of this energy distribution is given by the color index, *B* − *V*, which measures the star's magnitude in blue (*B*) and green-yellow (*V*) light by means of filters.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This difference in magnitude provides a measure of a star's temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Main-sequence stars are called dwarf stars, but this terminology is partly historical and can be somewhat confusing.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For the cooler stars, dwarfs such as red dwarfs, orange dwarfs, and yellow dwarfs are indeed much smaller and dimmer than other stars of those colors.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] However, for hotter blue and white stars, the difference in size and brightness between so-called "dwarf" stars that are on the main sequence and so-called "giant" stars that are not, becomes smaller.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For the hottest stars the difference is not directly observable and for these stars, the terms "dwarf" and "giant" refer to differences in spectral lines which indicate whether a star is on or off the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Nevertheless, very hot main-sequence stars are still sometimes called dwarfs, even though they have roughly the same size and brightness as the "giant" stars of that temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The common use of "dwarf" to mean the main sequence is confusing in another way because there are dwarf stars that are not main-sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For example, a white dwarf is the dead core left over after a star has shed its outer layers, and is much smaller than a main-sequence star, roughly the size of Earth.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] These represent the final evolutionary stage of many main-sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] where *σ* is the Stefan–Boltzmann constant.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] As the position of a star on the HR diagram shows its approximate luminosity, this relation can be used to estimate its radius.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The mass, radius, and luminosity of a star are closely interlinked, and their respective values can be approximated by three relations.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] First is the Stefan–Boltzmann law, which relates the luminosity *L*, the radius *R* and the surface temperature *T*eff.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Second is the mass–luminosity relation, which relates the luminosity *L* and the mass *M*.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Finally, the relationship between *M* and *R* is close to linear.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The ratio of *M* to *R* increases by a factor of only three over 2.5 orders of magnitude of *M*.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This relation is roughly proportional to the star's inner temperature *TI*, and its extremely slow increase reflects the fact that the rate of energy generation in the core strongly depends on this temperature, whereas it has to fit the mass-luminosity relation.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Thus, a too-high or too-low temperature will result in stellar instability.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A better approximation is to take *ε* = *L*/*M*, the energy generation rate per unit mass, as *ε* is proportional to *TI*15, where *TI* is the core temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This is suitable for stars at least as massive as the Sun, exhibiting the CNO cycle, and gives the better fit *R* ∝ *M*0.78.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The table below shows typical values for stars along the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The values of luminosity (*L*), radius (*R*), and mass (*M*) are relative to the Sun—a dwarf star with a spectral classification of G2 V.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The actual values for a star may vary by as much as 20–30% from the values listed below.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] All main-sequence stars have a core region where energy is generated by nuclear fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The temperature and density of this core are at the levels necessary to sustain the energy production that will support the remainder of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A reduction of energy production would cause the overlaying mass to compress the core, resulting in an increase in the fusion rate because of higher temperature and pressure.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Likewise, an increase in energy production would cause the star to expand, lowering the pressure at the core.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Thus the star forms a self-regulating system in hydrostatic equilibrium that is stable over the course of its main-sequence lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Main-sequence stars employ two types of hydrogen fusion processes, and the rate of energy generation from each type depends on the temperature in the core region.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Astronomers divide the main sequence into upper and lower parts, based on which of the two is the dominant fusion process.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In the lower main sequence, energy is primarily generated as the result of the proton–proton chain, which directly fuses hydrogen together in a series of stages to produce helium.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Stars in the upper main sequence have sufficiently high core temperatures to efficiently use the CNO cycle (see chart).
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This process uses atoms of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen as intermediaries in the process of fusing hydrogen into helium.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] At a stellar core temperature of 18 million kelvin, the PP process and CNO cycle are equally efficient, and each type generates half of the star's net luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] As this is the core temperature of a star with about 1.5 *M*☉, the upper main sequence consists of stars above this mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Thus, roughly speaking, stars of spectral class F or cooler belong to the lower main sequence, while A-type stars or hotter are upper main-sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The transition in primary energy production from one form to the other spans a range difference of less than a single solar mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In the Sun, a one solar-mass star, only 1.5% of the energy is generated by the CNO cycle.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] By contrast, stars with 1.8 *M*☉ or above generate almost their entire energy output through the CNO cycle.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The observed upper limit for a main-sequence star is 120–200 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The theoretical explanation for this limit is that stars above this mass can not radiate energy fast enough to remain stable, so any additional mass will be ejected in a series of pulsations until the star reaches a stable limit.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The lower limit for sustained proton-proton nuclear fusion is about 0.08 *M*☉ or 80 times the mass of Jupiter.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Below this threshold are sub-stellar objects that can not sustain hydrogen fusion, known as brown dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Because there is a temperature difference between the core and the surface, or photosphere, energy is transported outward.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The two modes for transporting this energy are radiation and convection.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A radiation zone, where energy is transported by radiation, is stable against convection and there is very little mixing of the plasma.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] By contrast, in a convection zone the energy is transported by bulk movement of plasma, with hotter material rising and cooler material descending.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Convection is a more efficient mode for carrying energy than radiation, but it will only occur under conditions that create a steep temperature gradient.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In massive stars (above 10 *M*☉) the rate of energy generation by the CNO cycle is very sensitive to temperature, so the fusion is highly concentrated at the core.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Consequently, there is a high temperature gradient in the core region, which results in a convection zone for more efficient energy transport.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This mixing of material around the core removes the helium ash from the hydrogen-burning region, allowing more of the hydrogen in the star to be consumed during the main-sequence lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The outer regions of a massive star transport energy by radiation, with little or no convection.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Intermediate-mass stars such as Sirius may transport energy primarily by radiation, with a small core convection region.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Medium-sized, low-mass stars like the Sun have a core region that is stable against convection, with a convection zone near the surface that mixes the outer layers.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This results in a steady buildup of a helium-rich core, surrounded by a hydrogen-rich outer region.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] By contrast, cool, very low-mass stars (below 0.4 *M*☉) are convective throughout.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Thus the helium produced at the core is distributed across the star, producing a relatively uniform atmosphere and a proportionately longer main-sequence lifespan.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] As non-fusing helium accumulates in the core of a main-sequence star, the reduction in the abundance of hydrogen per unit mass results in a gradual lowering of the fusion rate within that mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Since it is fusion-supplied power that maintains the pressure of the core and supports the higher layers of the star, the core gradually gets compressed.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This brings hydrogen-rich material into a shell around the helium-rich core at a depth where the pressure is sufficient for fusion to occur.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The high power output from this shell pushes the higher layers of the star further out.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This causes a gradual increase in the radius and consequently luminosity of the star over time.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For example, the luminosity of the early Sun was only about 70% of its current value.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] As a star ages it thus changes its position on the HR diagram.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This evolution is reflected in a broadening of the main sequence band which contains stars at various evolutionary stages.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Other factors that broaden the main sequence band on the HR diagram include uncertainty in the distance to stars and the presence of unresolved binary stars that can alter the observed stellar parameters.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] However, even perfect observation would show a fuzzy main sequence because mass is not the only parameter that affects a star's color and luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Variations in chemical composition caused by the initial abundances, the star's evolutionary status, interaction with a close companion, rapid rotation, or a magnetic field can all slightly change a main-sequence star's HR diagram position, to name just a few factors.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] As an example, there are metal-poor stars (with a very low abundance of elements with higher atomic numbers than helium) that lie just below the main sequence and are known as subdwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] These stars are fusing hydrogen in their cores and so they mark the lower edge of the main sequence fuzziness caused by variance in chemical composition.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A nearly vertical region of the HR diagram, known as the instability strip, is occupied by pulsating variable stars known as Cepheid variables.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] These stars vary in magnitude at regular intervals, giving them a pulsating appearance.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The strip intersects the upper part of the main sequence in the region of class *A* and *F* stars, which are between one and two solar masses.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Pulsating stars in this part of the instability strip intersecting the upper part of the main sequence are called Delta Scuti variables.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Main-sequence stars in this region experience only small changes in magnitude, so this variation is difficult to detect.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Other classes of unstable main-sequence stars, like Beta Cephei variables, are unrelated to this instability strip.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The total amount of energy that a star can generate through nuclear fusion of hydrogen is limited by the amount of hydrogen fuel that can be consumed at the core.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For a star in equilibrium, the thermal energy generated at the core must be at least equal to the energy radiated at the surface.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Since the luminosity gives the amount of energy radiated per unit time, the total life span can be estimated, to first approximation, as the total energy produced divided by the star's luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For a star with at least 0.5 *M*☉, when the hydrogen supply in its core is exhausted and it expands to become a red giant, it can start to fuse helium atoms to form carbon.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The energy output of the helium fusion process per unit mass is only about a tenth the energy output of the hydrogen process, and the luminosity of the star increases.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This results in a much shorter length of time in this stage compared to the main-sequence lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] (For example, the Sun is predicted to spend 130 million years burning helium, compared to about 12 billion years burning hydrogen.) Thus, about 90% of the observed stars above 0.5 *M*☉ will be on the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] On average, main-sequence stars are known to follow an empirical mass–luminosity relationship.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This relationship applies to main-sequence stars in the range 0.1–50 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The amount of fuel available for nuclear fusion is proportional to the mass of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Thus, the lifetime of a star on the main sequence can be estimated by comparing it to solar evolutionary models.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The Sun has been a main-sequence star for about 4.5 billion years and it will start to expand rapidly towards a red giant in 6.5 billion years, for a total main-sequence lifetime of roughly 1010 years.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] where *M* and *L* are the mass and luminosity of the star, respectively, $M_{\bigodot }$ is a solar mass, $L_{\bigodot }$ is the solar luminosity and $\tau _{\text{MS}}$ is the star's estimated main-sequence lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Although more massive stars have more fuel to burn and might intuitively be expected to last longer, they also radiate a proportionately greater amount with increased mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This is required by the stellar equation of state; for a massive star to maintain equilibrium, the outward pressure of radiated energy generated in the core not only must but *will* rise to match the titanic inward gravitational pressure of its envelope.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Thus, the most massive stars may remain on the main sequence for only a few million years, while stars with less than a tenth of a solar mass may last for over a trillion years.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The exact mass-luminosity relationship depends on how efficiently energy can be transported from the core to the surface.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A higher opacity has an insulating effect that retains more energy at the core, so the star does not need to produce as much energy to remain in hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] By contrast, a lower opacity means energy escapes more rapidly and the star must burn more fuel to remain in equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A sufficiently high opacity can result in energy transport via convection, which changes the conditions needed to remain in equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In high-mass main-sequence stars, the opacity is dominated by electron scattering, which is nearly constant with increasing temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Thus the luminosity only increases as the cube of the star's mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For stars below 10 *M*☉, the opacity becomes dependent on temperature, resulting in the luminosity varying approximately as the fourth power of the star's mass.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] For very low-mass stars, molecules in the atmosphere also contribute to the opacity.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Below about 0.5 *M*☉, the luminosity of the star varies as the mass to the power of 2.3, producing a flattening of the slope on a graph of mass versus luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Even these refinements are only an approximation, however, and the mass-luminosity relation can vary depending on a star's composition.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When a main-sequence star has consumed the hydrogen at its core, the loss of energy generation causes its gravitational collapse to resume and the star evolves off the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The path which the star follows across the HR diagram is called an evolutionary track.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] A track known as the zero age main sequence (ZAMS) is where stars of different masses begin their main sequence lives, while a track known as the terminal age main sequence (TAMS) is where stars of different masses end their main sequence lives when hydrogen is depleted in their cores.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] In stars more massive than 0.23 *M*☉, the hydrogen surrounding the helium core reaches sufficient temperature and pressure to undergo fusion, forming a hydrogen-burning shell and causing the outer layers of the star to expand and cool.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The stage as these stars move away from the main sequence is known as the subgiant branch; it is relatively brief and appears as a gap in the evolutionary track since few stars are observed at that point.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When the helium core of low-mass stars becomes degenerate, or the outer layers of intermediate-mass stars cool sufficiently to become opaque, their hydrogen shells increase in temperature and the stars start to become more luminous.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] This is known as the red-giant branch; it is a relatively long-lived stage and it appears prominently in H–R diagrams.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] These stars will eventually end their lives as white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The most massive stars do not become red giants; instead, their cores quickly become hot enough to fuse helium and eventually heavier elements and they are known as supergiants.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] They follow approximately horizontal evolutionary tracks from the main sequence across the top of the H–R diagram.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Supergiants are relatively rare and do not show prominently on most H–R diagrams.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] Their cores will eventually collapse, usually leading to a supernova and leaving behind either a neutron star or black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] When a cluster of stars is formed at about the same time, the main-sequence lifespan of these stars will depend on their individual masses.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The most massive stars will leave the main sequence first, followed in sequence by stars of ever lower masses.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] The position where stars in the cluster are leaving the main sequence is known as the turnoff point.
[src:stellar-physics/main-sequence] By knowing the main-sequence lifespan of stars at this point, it becomes possible to estimate the age of the cluster.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Nuclear fusion powers a star for most of its existence.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Initially the energy is generated by the fusion of hydrogen atoms at the core of the main-sequence star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Later, as the preponderance of atoms at the core becomes helium, stars like the Sun begin to fuse hydrogen along a spherical shell surrounding the core.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] This process causes the star to gradually grow in size, passing through the subgiant stage until it reaches the red-giant phase.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Stars with at least half the mass of the Sun can also begin to generate energy through the fusion of helium at their core, whereas more-massive stars can fuse heavier elements along a series of concentric shells.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Once a star like the Sun has exhausted its nuclear fuel, its core collapses into a dense white dwarf and the outer layers are expelled as a planetary nebula.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Stars with around ten or more times the mass of the Sun can explode in a supernova as their inert iron cores collapse into an extremely dense neutron star or black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Although the universe is not old enough for any of the smallest red dwarfs to have reached the end of their existence, stellar models suggest they will slowly become brighter and hotter before running out of hydrogen fuel and becoming low-mass white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Stellar evolution is not studied by observing the life of a single star, as most stellar changes occur too slowly to be detected, even over many centuries.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Instead, astrophysicists come to understand how stars evolve by observing numerous stars at various points in their lifetime, and by simulating stellar structure using computer models.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Stellar evolution starts with the gravitational collapse of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Typical giant molecular clouds are roughly 100 light-years (9.5×1014 km) across and contain up to 6,000,000 solar masses (1.2×1037 kg).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] As it collapses, a giant molecular cloud breaks into smaller and smaller pieces.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In each of these fragments, the collapsing gas releases gravitational potential energy as heat.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] As its temperature and pressure increase, a fragment condenses into a rotating ball of superhot gas known as a protostar.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Filamentary structures are truly ubiquitous in the molecular cloud.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Dense molecular filaments will fragment into gravitationally bound cores, which are the precursors of stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Continuous accretion of gas, geometrical bending, and magnetic fields may control the detailed fragmentation manner of the filaments.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In supercritical filaments, observations have revealed quasi-periodic chains of dense cores with spacing comparable to the filament inner width, and embedded two protostars with gas outflows.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A protostar continues to grow by accretion of gas and dust from the molecular cloud, becoming a pre-main-sequence star as it reaches its final mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Further development is determined by its mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Mass is typically compared to the mass of the Sun: 1.0 *M*☉ (2.0×1030 kg) means 1 solar mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Protostars are encompassed in dust, and are thus more readily visible at infrared wavelengths.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Observations from the Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer (WISE) have been especially important for unveiling numerous galactic protostars and their parent star clusters.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Protostars with masses less than roughly 0.08 *M*☉ (1.6×1029 kg) never reach temperatures high enough for nuclear fusion of hydrogen to begin.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The International Astronomical Union defines brown dwarfs as stars massive enough to fuse deuterium at some point in their lives (13 Jupiter masses (*M*J), 2.5 × 1028 kg, or 0.0125 *M*☉).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Objects smaller than 13 *M*J are classified as sub-brown dwarfs (but if they orbit around another stellar object they are classified as planets).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Both types, deuterium-burning and not, shine dimly and fade away slowly, cooling gradually over hundreds of millions of years.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] , which will be the last phase in which the Sun undergoes fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] For a more-massive protostar, the core temperature will eventually reach 10 million kelvin, initiating the proton–proton chain reaction and allowing hydrogen to fuse, first to deuterium and then to helium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In stars of slightly over 1 *M*☉ (2.0×1030 kg), the carbon–nitrogen–oxygen fusion reaction (CNO cycle) contributes a large portion of the energy generation.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The onset of nuclear fusion leads relatively quickly to a hydrostatic equilibrium in which energy released by the core maintains a high gas pressure, balancing the weight of the star's matter and preventing further gravitational collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The star thus evolves rapidly to a stable state, beginning the main-sequence phase of its evolution.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A new star will sit at a specific point on the main sequence of the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, with the main-sequence spectral type depending upon the mass of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Small, relatively cold, low-mass red dwarfs fuse hydrogen slowly and will remain on the main sequence for hundreds of billions of years or longer, whereas massive, hot O-type stars will leave the main sequence after just a few million years.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A mid-sized yellow dwarf star, like the Sun, will remain on the main sequence for about 10 billion years.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The Sun is thought to be in the middle of its main sequence lifespan.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A star may gain a protoplanetary disk, which furthermore can develop into a planetary system.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Eventually the star's core exhausts its supply of hydrogen and the star begins to evolve off the main sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Without the outward radiation pressure generated by the fusion of hydrogen to counteract the force of gravity, the core contracts until either electron degeneracy pressure becomes sufficient to oppose gravity or the core becomes hot enough (around 100 MK) for helium fusion to begin.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Which of these happens first depends upon the star's mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] What happens after a low-mass star ceases to produce energy through fusion has not been directly observed; the universe is around 13.8 billion years old, which is less time (by several orders of magnitude, in some cases) than it takes for fusion to cease in such stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Recent astrophysical models suggest that red dwarfs of 0.1 *M*☉ may stay on the main sequence for some six to twelve trillion years, gradually increasing in both temperature and luminosity, and take several hundred billion years more to collapse, slowly, into a white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Such stars will not become red giants as the whole star is a convection zone and it will not develop a degenerate helium core with a shell burning hydrogen.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Instead, hydrogen fusion will proceed until almost the whole star is helium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Slightly more massive stars do expand into red giants, but their helium cores are not massive enough to reach the temperatures required for helium fusion so they never reach the tip of the red-giant branch.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] When hydrogen shell burning finishes, these stars move directly off the red-giant branch like a post-asymptotic-giant-branch (AGB) star, but at lower luminosity, to become a white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A star with an initial mass about 0.6 *M*☉ will be able to reach temperatures high enough to fuse helium, and these "mid-sized" stars go on to further stages of evolution beyond the red-giant branch.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Stars of roughly 0.6–10 *M*☉ become red giants, which are large non-main-sequence stars of stellar classification K or M.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Red giants lie along the right edge of the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram due to their red color and large luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Examples include Aldebaran in the constellation Taurus and Arcturus in the constellation of Boötes.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Between these two phases, stars spend a period on the horizontal branch with a helium-fusing core.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Many of these helium-fusing stars cluster towards the cool end of the horizontal branch as K-type giants and are referred to as red clump giants.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] When a star exhausts the hydrogen in its core, it leaves the main sequence and begins to fuse hydrogen in a shell outside the core.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The core increases in mass as the shell produces more helium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Depending on the mass of the helium core, this continues for several million to one or two billion years, with the star expanding and cooling at a similar or slightly lower luminosity to its main sequence state.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Eventually either the core becomes degenerate, in stars around the mass of the sun, or the outer layers cool sufficiently to become opaque, in more massive stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Either of these changes cause the hydrogen shell to increase in temperature and the luminosity of the star to increase, at which point the star expands onto the red-giant branch.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The expanding outer layers of the star are convective, with the material being mixed by turbulence from near the fusing regions up to the surface of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] For all but the lowest-mass stars, the fused material has remained deep in the stellar interior prior to this point, so the convecting envelope makes fusion products visible at the star's surface for the first time.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] At this stage of evolution, the results are subtle, with the largest effects, alterations to the isotopes of hydrogen and helium, being unobservable.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The effects of the CNO cycle appear at the surface during the first dredge-up, with lower 12C/13C ratios and altered proportions of carbon and nitrogen.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These are detectable with spectroscopy and have been measured for many evolved stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The helium core continues to grow on the red-giant branch.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] It is no longer in thermal equilibrium, either degenerate or above the Schönberg–Chandrasekhar limit, so it increases in temperature which causes the rate of fusion in the hydrogen shell to increase.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The star increases in luminosity towards the tip of the red-giant branch.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Red-giant-branch stars with a degenerate helium core all reach the tip with very similar core masses and very similar luminosities, although the more massive of the red giants become hot enough to ignite helium fusion before that point.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In the helium cores of stars in the 0.6 to 2.0 solar mass range, which are largely supported by electron degeneracy pressure, helium fusion will ignite on a timescale of days in a helium flash.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In the nondegenerate cores of more massive stars, the ignition of helium fusion occurs relatively slowly with no flash.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The nuclear power released during the helium flash is very large, on the order of 108 times the luminosity of the Sun for a few days and 1011 times the luminosity of the Sun (roughly the luminosity of the Milky Way Galaxy) for a few seconds.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] However, the energy is consumed by the thermal expansion of the initially degenerate core and thus cannot be seen from outside the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Due to the expansion of the core, the hydrogen fusion in the overlying layers slows and total energy generation decreases.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The star contracts, although not all the way to the main sequence, and it migrates to the horizontal branch on the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, gradually shrinking in radius and increasing its surface temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Core helium flash stars evolve to the red end of the horizontal branch but do not migrate to higher temperatures before they gain a degenerate carbon-oxygen core and start helium shell burning.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These stars are often observed as a red clump of stars in the colour-magnitude diagram of a cluster, hotter and less luminous than the red giants.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Higher-mass stars with larger helium cores move along the horizontal branch to higher temperatures, some becoming unstable pulsating stars in the yellow instability strip (RR Lyrae variables), whereas some become even hotter and can form a blue tail or blue hook to the horizontal branch.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The morphology of the horizontal branch depends on parameters such as metallicity, age, and helium content, but the exact details are still being modelled.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] After a star has consumed the helium at the core, hydrogen and helium fusion continues in shells around a hot core of carbon and oxygen.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The star follows the asymptotic giant branch on the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, paralleling the original red-giant evolution, but with even faster energy generation (which lasts for a shorter time).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Although helium is being burnt in a shell, the majority of the energy is produced by hydrogen burning in a shell further from the core of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Helium from these hydrogen burning shells drops towards the center of the star and periodically the energy output from the helium shell increases dramatically.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] This is known as a thermal pulse and they occur towards the end of the asymptotic-giant-branch phase, sometimes even into the post-asymptotic-giant-branch phase.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Depending on mass and composition, there may be several to hundreds of thermal pulses.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] There is a phase on the ascent of the asymptotic-giant-branch where a deep convective zone forms and can bring carbon from the core to the surface.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] This is known as the second dredge up, and in some stars there may even be a third dredge up.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In this way a carbon star is formed, very cool and strongly reddened stars showing strong carbon lines in their spectra.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A process known as hot bottom burning may convert carbon into oxygen and nitrogen before it can be dredged to the surface, and the interaction between these processes determines the observed luminosities and spectra of carbon stars in particular clusters.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Another well known class of asymptotic-giant-branch stars is the Mira variables, which pulsate with well-defined periods of tens to hundreds of days and large amplitudes up to about 10 magnitudes (in the visual, total luminosity changes by a much smaller amount).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In more-massive stars the stars become more luminous and the pulsation period is longer, leading to enhanced mass loss, and the stars become heavily obscured at visual wavelengths.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These stars can be observed as OH/IR stars, pulsating in the infrared and showing OH maser activity.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These stars are clearly oxygen rich, in contrast to the carbon stars, but both must be produced by dredge ups.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These mid-range stars ultimately reach the tip of the asymptotic-giant-branch and run out of fuel for shell burning.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] They are not sufficiently massive to start full-scale carbon fusion, so they contract again, going through a period of post-asymptotic-giant-branch superwind to produce a planetary nebula with an extremely hot central star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The central star then cools to a white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The expelled gas is relatively rich in heavy elements created within the star and may be particularly oxygen or carbon enriched, depending on the type of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The gas builds up in an expanding shell called a circumstellar envelope and cools as it moves away from the star, allowing dust particles and molecules to form.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] With the high infrared energy input from the central star, ideal conditions are formed in these circumstellar envelopes for maser excitation.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] It is possible for thermal pulses to be produced once post-asymptotic-giant-branch evolution has begun, producing a variety of unusual and poorly understood stars known as born-again asymptotic-giant-branch stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These may result in extreme horizontal-branch stars (subdwarf B stars), hydrogen deficient post-asymptotic-giant-branch stars, variable planetary nebula central stars, and R Coronae Borealis variables.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In massive stars, the core is already large enough at the onset of the hydrogen burning shell that helium ignition will occur before electron degeneracy pressure has a chance to become prevalent.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Thus, when these stars expand and cool, they do not brighten as dramatically as lower-mass stars; however, they were more luminous on the main sequence and they evolve to highly luminous supergiants.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Their cores become massive enough that they cannot support themselves by electron degeneracy and will eventually collapse to produce a neutron star or black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The largest stars of the current generation are about 100–150 *M*☉ because the outer layers would be expelled by the extreme radiation.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The core of a massive star, defined as the region depleted of hydrogen, grows hotter and denser as it accretes material from the fusion of hydrogen outside the core.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In sufficiently massive stars, the core reaches temperatures and densities high enough to fuse carbon and heavier elements via the alpha process.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] At the end of helium fusion, the core of a star consists primarily of carbon and oxygen.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In stars heavier than about 8 *M*☉, the carbon ignites and fuses to form neon, sodium, and magnesium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Stars somewhat less massive may partially ignite carbon, but they are unable to fully fuse the carbon before electron degeneracy sets in, and these stars will eventually leave an oxygen-neon-magnesium white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The exact mass limit for full carbon burning depends on several factors such as metallicity and the detailed mass lost on the asymptotic giant branch, but is approximately 8–9 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] After carbon burning is complete, the core of these stars reaches about 2.5 *M*☉ and becomes hot enough for heavier elements to fuse.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Before oxygen starts to fuse, neon begins to capture electrons which triggers neon burning.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] For a range of stars of approximately 8-12 *M*☉, this process is unstable and creates runaway fusion resulting in an electron capture supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In more massive stars, the fusion of neon proceeds without a runaway deflagration.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] This is followed in turn by complete oxygen burning and silicon burning, producing a core consisting largely of iron-peak elements.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Surrounding the core are shells of lighter elements still undergoing fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The timescale for complete fusion of a carbon core to an iron core is so short, just a few hundred years, that the outer layers of the star are unable to react and the appearance of the star is largely unchanged.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The iron core grows until it reaches an *effective Chandrasekhar mass*, higher than the formal Chandrasekhar mass due to various corrections for the relativistic effects, entropy, charge, and the surrounding envelope.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The effective Chandrasekhar mass for an iron core varies from about 1.34 *M*☉ in the least massive red supergiants to more than 1.8 *M*☉ in more massive stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Once this mass is reached, electrons begin to be captured into the iron-peak nuclei and the core becomes unable to support itself.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The core collapses and the star is destroyed, either in a supernova or direct collapse to a black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] When the core of a massive star collapses, it will form a neutron star, or in the case of cores that exceed the Tolman–Oppenheimer–Volkoff limit, a black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Through a process that is not completely understood, some of the gravitational potential energy released by this core collapse is converted into a Type Ib, Type Ic, or Type II supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] It is known that the core collapse produces a massive surge of neutrinos, as observed with supernova SN 1987A.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Electron capture in very dense parts of the infalling matter may produce additional neutrons.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Because some of the rebounding matter is bombarded by the neutrons, some of its nuclei capture them, creating a spectrum of heavier-than-iron material including the radioactive elements up to (and likely beyond) uranium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Neither abundance alone matches that found in the Solar System, so both supernovae, neutron star mergers and ejection of elements from red giants are required to explain the observed abundance of heavy elements and isotopes thereof.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The energy transferred from collapse of the core to rebounding material not only generates heavy elements, but provides for their acceleration well beyond escape velocity, thus causing a Type Ib, Type Ic, or Type II supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Current understanding of this energy transfer is still not satisfactory; although current computer models of Type Ib, Type Ic, and Type II supernovae account for part of the energy transfer, they are not able to account for enough energy transfer to produce the observed ejection of material.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] However, neutrino oscillations may play an important role in the energy transfer problem as they not only affect the energy available in a particular flavour of neutrinos but also through other general-relativistic effects on neutrinos.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The most massive stars that exist today may be completely destroyed by a supernova with an energy greatly exceeding its gravitational binding energy.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] This rare event, caused by pair-instability, leaves behind no black hole remnant.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In the past history of the universe, some stars were even larger than the largest that exists today, and they would immediately collapse into a black hole at the end of their lives, due to photodisintegration.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] After a star has burned out its fuel supply, its remnants can take one of three forms, depending on the mass during its lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] For a star of 1 *M*☉, the resulting white dwarf is of about 0.6 *M*☉, compressed into approximately the volume of the Earth.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] White dwarfs are stable because the inward pull of gravity is balanced by the degeneracy pressure of the star's electrons, a consequence of the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Electron degeneracy pressure provides a rather soft limit against further compression; therefore, for a given chemical composition, white dwarfs of higher mass have a smaller volume.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] With no fuel left to burn, the star radiates its remaining heat into space for billions of years.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A white dwarf is very hot when it first forms, more than 100,000 K at the surface and even hotter in its interior.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] It is so hot that a lot of its energy is lost in the form of neutrinos for the first 10 million years of its existence and will have lost most of its energy after a billion years.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The chemical composition of the white dwarf depends upon its mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A star of mass on the order of magnitude of the Sun will be unable to ignite carbon fusion, and will produce a white dwarf composed chiefly of carbon and oxygen, and of mass too low to collapse unless matter is added to it later (see below).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A star of less than about half the mass of the Sun will be unable to ignite helium fusion (as noted earlier), and will produce a white dwarf composed chiefly of helium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] In the end, all that remains is a cold dark mass sometimes called a black dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] However, the universe is not old enough for any black dwarfs to exist yet.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] If the white dwarf's mass increases above the Chandrasekhar limit, which is 1.4 *M*☉ for a white dwarf composed chiefly of carbon, oxygen, neon, and/or magnesium, then electron degeneracy pressure fails due to electron capture and the star collapses.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Depending upon the chemical composition and pre-collapse temperature in the center, this will lead either to collapse into a neutron star or runaway ignition of carbon and oxygen.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Heavier elements favor continued core collapse, because they require a higher temperature to ignite, because electron capture onto these elements and their fusion products is easier; higher core temperatures favor runaway nuclear reaction, which halts core collapse and leads to a Type Ia supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These supernovae may be many times brighter than the Type II supernova marking the death of a massive star, even though the latter has the greater total energy release.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] This instability to collapse means that no white dwarf more massive than approximately 1.4 *M*☉ can exist (with a possible minor exception for very rapidly spinning white dwarfs, whose centrifugal force due to rotation partially counteracts the weight of their matter).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Mass transfer in a binary system may cause an initially stable white dwarf to surpass the Chandrasekhar limit.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] If a white dwarf forms a close binary system with another star, hydrogen from the larger companion may accrete around and onto a white dwarf until it gets hot enough to fuse in a runaway reaction at its surface, although the white dwarf remains below the Chandrasekhar limit.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Ordinarily, atoms are mostly electron clouds by volume, with very compact nuclei at the center (proportionally, if atoms were the size of a football stadium, their nuclei would be the size of dust mites).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] When a stellar core collapses, the pressure causes electrons and protons to fuse by electron capture.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Without electrons, which keep nuclei apart, the neutrons collapse into a dense ball (in some ways like a giant atomic nucleus), with a thin overlying layer of degenerate matter (chiefly iron unless matter of different composition is added later).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The neutrons resist further compression by the Pauli exclusion principle, in a way analogous to electron degeneracy pressure, but stronger.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] These stars, known as neutron stars, are extremely small—on the order of radius 10 km, no bigger than the size of a large city—and are phenomenally dense.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Their period of rotation shortens dramatically as the stars shrink (due to conservation of angular momentum); observed rotational periods of neutron stars range from about 1.5 milliseconds (over 600 revolutions per second) to several seconds.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] When these rapidly rotating stars' magnetic poles are aligned with the Earth, there is a detectable pulse of radiation each revolution.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Such neutron stars are called pulsars, and were the first neutron stars to be discovered.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Though electromagnetic radiation detected from pulsars is most often in the form of radio waves, pulsars have also been detected at visible, X-ray, and gamma ray wavelengths.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] If the mass of the stellar remnant is high enough, the neutron degeneracy pressure will be insufficient to prevent collapse below the Schwarzschild radius.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The stellar remnant thus becomes a black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The mass at which this occurs is not known with certainty, but is currently estimated at between 2 and 3 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Black holes are predicted by the theory of general relativity.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] According to classical general relativity, no matter or information can flow from the interior of a black hole to an outside observer, although quantum effects may allow deviations from this strict rule.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The existence of black holes in the universe is well supported, both theoretically and by astronomical observation.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Resolution of these uncertainties requires the analysis of more supernovae and supernova remnants.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] A stellar evolutionary model is a mathematical model that can be used to compute the evolutionary phases of a star from its formation until it becomes a remnant.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The mass and chemical composition of the star are used as the inputs, and the luminosity and surface temperature are the only constraints.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] The model formulae are based upon the physical understanding of the star, usually under the assumption of hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Extensive computer calculations are then run to determine the changing state of the star over time, yielding a table of data that can be used to determine the evolutionary track of the star across the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, along with other evolving properties.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-evolution] Accurate models can be used to estimate the current age of a star by comparing its physical properties with those of stars along a matching evolutionary track.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In astrophysics, **stellar nucleosynthesis** is the creation of chemical elements by nuclear fusion reactions within stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Stellar nucleosynthesis has occurred since the original creation of hydrogen, helium and lithium during the Big Bang.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] As a predictive theory, it yields accurate estimates of the observed abundances of the elements.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] It explains why the observed abundances of elements change over time and why some elements and their isotopes are much more abundant than others.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The theory was initially proposed by Fred Hoyle in 1946, who later refined it in 1954.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Further advances were made, especially to nucleosynthesis by neutron capture of the elements heavier than iron, by Margaret and Geoffrey Burbidge, William Alfred Fowler and Fred Hoyle in their famous 1957 B2FH paper, which became one of the most heavily cited papers in astrophysics history.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Stars evolve because of changes in their composition (the abundance of their constituent elements) over their lifespans, first by burning hydrogen (main sequence star), then helium (horizontal branch star), and progressively burning higher elements.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] However, this does not by itself significantly alter the abundances of elements in the universe as the elements are contained within the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Later in its life, a low-mass star will slowly eject its atmosphere via stellar wind, forming a planetary nebula, while a higher–mass star will eject mass via a sudden catastrophic event called a supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The term supernova nucleosynthesis is used to describe the creation of elements during the explosion of a massive star or white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The advanced sequence of burning fuels is driven by gravitational collapse and its associated heating, resulting in the subsequent burning of carbon, oxygen and silicon.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] However, most of the nucleosynthesis in the mass range *A* = 28–56 (from silicon to nickel) is actually caused by the upper layers of the star collapsing onto the core, creating a compressional shock wave rebounding outward.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The shock front briefly raises temperatures by roughly 50%, thereby causing furious burning for about a second.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This final burning in massive stars, called *explosive nucleosynthesis* or supernova nucleosynthesis, is the final epoch of stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] A stimulus to the development of the theory of nucleosynthesis was the discovery early in the 20th century of regular variations in the abundances of elements found in the universe according to the Oddo–Harkins rule.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The need for a physical description was already inspired by the relative abundances of the chemical elements in the Solar System.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Those abundances, when plotted on a graph as a function of the atomic number of the element, have a jagged sawtooth shape that varies by factors of tens of millions (see history of nucleosynthesis theory).
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This suggested a natural process that is not random.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In 1920, Arthur Eddington, on the basis of the precise measurements of atomic masses by F.W.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Aston and a preliminary suggestion by Jean Perrin, proposed that stars obtained their energy from nuclear fusion of hydrogen to form helium and raised the possibility that the heavier elements are produced in stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This was a preliminary step toward the idea of stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In the following decade the Gamow factor was used by Robert d'Escourt Atkinson and Fritz Houtermans and later by Edward Teller and Gamow himself to derive the rate at which nuclear reactions would occur at the high temperatures believed to exist in stellar interiors.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In a 1939 paper entitled "Energy Production in Stars", Hans Bethe analyzed the different possibilities for reactions by which hydrogen is fused into helium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] He defined two processes that he believed to be the sources of energy in stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The first one, the proton–proton chain reaction, is the dominant energy source in stars with masses up to about the mass of the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The second process, the carbon–nitrogen–oxygen cycle, which was also considered by Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker in 1938, is more important in more massive main-sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] These works concerned the energy generation capable of keeping stars hot.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Bethe's two papers did not address the creation of heavier nuclei, however.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] That theory was begun by Fred Hoyle in 1946 with his argument that a collection of very hot nuclei would assemble thermodynamically into iron.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Hoyle followed that in 1954 with a paper describing how advanced fusion stages within massive stars would synthesize the elements from carbon to iron in mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Hoyle's theory was extended to other processes, beginning with the publication of the 1957 review paper "Synthesis of the Elements in Stars" by Margaret Burbidge, Geoffrey Burbidge, William Alfred Fowler and Fred Hoyle, more commonly referred to as the B2FH paper.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This review paper synthesized information from across fields of nuclear physics, stellar evolution and abundance of the elements to create the foundation of a theory of stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Cameron, working independently showed the Oddo–Harkins even-odd abundance rule would follow from processes outlined by the B2FH paper.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Clayton calculated the first time-dependent models of the *s*-process in 1961 and of the *r*-process in 1965, as well as of the burning of silicon into the abundant alpha-particle nuclei and iron-group elements in 1968, and discovered radiogenic chronologies for determining the age of the elements.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The helium nucleus is released at the top-left step.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Hydrogen fusion (nuclear fusion of four protons to form a helium-4 nucleus) is the dominant process that generates energy in the cores of main-sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] It is also called "hydrogen burning", which should not be confused with the chemical combustion of hydrogen in an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] There are two predominant processes by which stellar hydrogen fusion occurs: the proton–proton chain and the carbon–nitrogen–oxygen (CNO) cycle.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Ninety percent of all stars, with the exception of white dwarfs, are fusing hydrogen by these two processes.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In the cores of lower-mass main-sequence stars such as the Sun, the dominant energy production process is the proton–proton chain reaction.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This creates a helium-4 nucleus through a sequence of reactions that begin with the fusion of two protons to form a deuterium nucleus (one proton plus one neutron) along with an ejected positron and neutrino.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In each complete fusion cycle, the proton–proton chain reaction releases about 26.2 MeV.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] For stars above 35% of the Sun's mass, the energy flux toward the surface is sufficiently low and energy transfer from the core region remains by radiative heat transfer, rather than by convective heat transfer.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] As a result, there is little mixing of fresh hydrogen into the core or fusion products outward.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In higher-mass stars, the dominant energy production process is the CNO cycle, which is a catalytic cycle that uses nuclei of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen as intermediaries and in the end produces a helium nucleus as with the proton–proton chain.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] During a complete CNO cycle, 25.0 MeV of energy is released.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The difference in energy production of this cycle, compared to the proton–proton chain reaction, is accounted for by the energy lost through neutrino emission.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] CNO cycle is highly sensitive to temperature, with rates proportional to the 16th to 20th power of the temperature; a 10% increase in temperature would result in a 350% increase in energy production.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] About 90% of the CNO cycle energy generation occurs within the inner 15% of the star's mass, hence it is strongly concentrated at the core.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This results in such an intense outward energy flux that convective energy transfer becomes more important than does radiative transfer.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] As a result, the core region becomes a convection zone, which stirs the hydrogen fusion region and keeps it well mixed with the surrounding proton-rich region.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This core convection occurs in stars where the CNO cycle contributes more than 20% of the total energy.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] As the star ages and the core temperature increases, the region occupied by the convection zone slowly shrinks from 20% of the mass down to the inner 8% of the mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The Sun produces on the order of 1% of its energy from the CNO cycle.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The type of hydrogen fusion process that dominates in a star is determined by the temperature dependency differences between the two reactions.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The proton–proton chain reaction starts at temperatures about 4×106 K, making it the dominant fusion mechanism in smaller stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] A self-maintaining CNO chain requires a higher temperature of approximately 1.6×107 K, but thereafter it increases more rapidly in efficiency as the temperature rises, than does the proton–proton reaction.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Above approximately 1.7×107 K, the CNO cycle becomes the dominant source of energy.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This temperature is achieved in the cores of main-sequence stars with at least 1.3 times the mass of the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The Sun itself has a core temperature of about 1.57×107 K.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] As a main-sequence star ages, the core temperature will rise, resulting in a steadily increasing contribution from its CNO cycle.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Main sequence stars accumulate helium in their cores as a result of hydrogen fusion, but the core does not become hot enough to initiate helium fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Helium fusion first begins when a star leaves the red giant branch after accumulating sufficient helium in its core to ignite it.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In stars around the mass of the Sun, this begins at the tip of the red giant branch with a helium flash from a degenerate helium core, and the star moves to the horizontal branch where it burns helium in its core.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] More massive stars ignite helium in their core without a flash and execute a blue loop before reaching the asymptotic giant branch.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Such a star initially moves away from the AGB toward bluer colours, then loops back again to what is called the Hayashi track.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] An important consequence of blue loops is that they give rise to classical Cepheid variables, of central importance in determining distances in the Milky Way and to nearby galaxies.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Despite the name, stars on a blue loop from the red giant branch are typically not blue in colour but are rather yellow giants, possibly Cepheid variables.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] They fuse helium until the core is largely carbon and oxygen.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] The most massive stars become supergiants when they leave the main sequence and quickly start helium fusion as they become red supergiants.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] After the helium is exhausted in the core of a star, helium fusion will continue in a shell around the carbon–oxygen core.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In all cases, helium is fused to carbon via the triple-alpha process, i.e., three helium nuclei are transformed into carbon via 8Be.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] This can then form oxygen, neon, and heavier elements via the alpha process.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] In this way, the alpha process preferentially produces elements with even numbers of protons by the capture of helium nuclei.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Elements with odd numbers of protons are formed by other fusion pathways.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Semi-classically, the cross section is proportional to ${\textstyle \pi \,\lambda ^{2}}$ , where ${\textstyle \lambda =h/p}$ is the de Broglie wavelength.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Thus semi-classically the cross section is proportional to ${\textstyle {\frac {E}{m}}=c^{2}}$ .
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Values of *S*(*E*0) are typically 10−3 – 103 keV·b, but are damped by a huge factor when involving a beta decay, due to the relation between the intermediate bound state (e.g. diproton) half-life and the beta decay half-life, as in the proton–proton chain reaction.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Note that typical core temperatures in main-sequence stars (the Sun) give *kT* of the order of 1 keV: ${\textstyle \log _{10}kT=-16+\log _{10}2.17}$ .
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Thus, the limiting reaction in the CNO cycle, proton capture by 14 7N, has *S*(*E*0) ~ *S*(0) = 3.5 keV·b, while the limiting reaction in the proton–proton chain reaction, the creation of deuterium from two protons, has a much lower *S*(*E*0) ~ *S*(0) = 4×10−22 keV·b.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-nucleosynthesis] Incidentally, since the former reaction has a much higher Gamow factor, and due to the relative abundance of elements in typical stars, the two reaction rates are equal at a temperature value that is within the core temperature ranges of main-sequence stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] For energy transport refer to Radiative transfer.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Different layers of the stars transport heat up and outwards in different ways, primarily convection and radiative transfer, but thermal conduction is important in white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Convection is the dominant mode of energy transport when the temperature gradient is steep enough so that a given parcel of gas within the star will continue to rise if it rises slightly via an adiabatic process.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] In this case, the rising parcel is buoyant and continues to rise if it is warmer than the surrounding gas; if the rising parcel is cooler than the surrounding gas, it will fall back to its original height.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] In regions with a low temperature gradient and a low enough opacity to allow energy transport via radiation, radiation is the dominant mode of energy transport.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The internal structure of a main sequence star depends upon the mass of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] In stars with masses of 0.3–1.5 solar masses (*M*☉), including the Sun, hydrogen-to-helium fusion occurs primarily via proton–proton chains, which do not establish a steep temperature gradient.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Thus, radiation dominates in the inner portion of solar mass stars.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The outer portion of solar mass stars is cool enough that hydrogen is neutral and thus opaque to ultraviolet photons, so convection dominates.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Therefore, solar mass stars have radiative cores with convective envelopes in the outer portion of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] In massive stars (greater than about 1.5 *M*☉), the core temperature is above about 1.8×107 K, so hydrogen-to-helium fusion occurs primarily via the CNO cycle.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] In the CNO cycle, the energy generation rate scales as the temperature to the 15th power, whereas the rate scales as the temperature to the 4th power in the proton-proton chains.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Due to the strong temperature sensitivity of the CNO cycle, the temperature gradient in the inner portion of the star is steep enough to make the core convective.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] In the outer portion of the star, the temperature gradient is shallower but the temperature is high enough that the hydrogen is nearly fully ionized, so the star remains transparent to ultraviolet radiation.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Thus, massive stars have a radiative envelope.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The lowest mass main sequence stars have no radiation zone; the dominant energy transport mechanism throughout the star is convection.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The simplest commonly used model of stellar structure is the spherically symmetric quasi-static model, which assumes that a star is in a steady state and that it is spherically symmetric.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] It contains four basic first-order differential equations: two represent how matter and pressure vary with radius; two represent how temperature and luminosity vary with radius.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The star is assumed to be in local thermodynamic equilibrium (LTE) so the temperature is identical for matter and photons.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] First is a statement of *hydrostatic equilibrium:* the outward force due to the pressure gradient within the star is exactly balanced by the inward force due to gravity.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] This is sometimes referred to as stellar equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] where $m(r)$ is the cumulative mass inside the shell at r and *G* is the gravitational constant.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Integrating the mass continuity equation from the star center ( $r=0$ ) to the radius of the star ( $r=R$ ) yields the total mass of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] where $\epsilon _{\nu }$ is the luminosity produced in the form of neutrinos (which usually escape the star without interacting with ordinary matter) per unit mass.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Outside the core of the star, where nuclear reactions occur, no energy is generated, so the luminosity is constant.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The energy transport equation takes differing forms depending upon the mode of energy transport.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] where $\kappa$ is the opacity of the matter, $\sigma$ is the Stefan–Boltzmann constant, and the Boltzmann constant is set to one.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The case of convective energy transport does not have a known rigorous mathematical formulation, and involves turbulence in the gas.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Convective energy transport is usually modeled using mixing length theory.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] This treats the gas in the star as containing discrete elements which roughly retain the temperature, density, and pressure of their surroundings but move through the star as far as a characteristic length, called the *mixing length*.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] where $\gamma =c_{p}/c_{v}$ is the adiabatic index, the ratio of specific heats in the gas.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] (For a fully ionized ideal gas, $\gamma =5/3$ .) When the convection is not adiabatic, the true temperature gradient is not given by this equation.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] For example, in the Sun the convection at the base of the convection zone, near the core, is adiabatic but that near the surface is not.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The mixing length theory contains two free parameters which must be set to make the model fit observations, so it is a phenomenological theory rather than a rigorous mathematical formulation.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Also required are the equations of state, relating the pressure, opacity and energy generation rate to other local variables appropriate for the material, such as temperature, density, chemical composition, etc.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Relevant equations of state for pressure may have to include the perfect gas law, radiation pressure, pressure due to degenerate electrons, etc.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Opacity cannot be expressed exactly by a single formula.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] It is calculated for various compositions at specific densities and temperatures and presented in tabular form.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Stellar structure *codes* (meaning computer programs calculating the model's variables) either interpolate in a density-temperature grid to obtain the opacity needed, or use a fitting function based on the tabulated values.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] A similar situation occurs for accurate calculations of the pressure equation of state.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Finally, the nuclear energy generation rate is computed from nuclear physics experiments, using *reaction networks* to compute reaction rates for each individual reaction step and equilibrium abundances for each isotope in the gas.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Combined with a set of boundary conditions, a solution of these equations completely describes the behavior of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Although nowadays stellar evolution models describe the main features of color–magnitude diagrams, important improvements have to be made in order to remove uncertainties which are linked to the limited knowledge of transport phenomena.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The most difficult challenge remains the numerical treatment of turbulence.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Some research teams are developing simplified modelling of turbulence in 3D calculations.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The above simplified model is not adequate without modification in situations when the composition changes are sufficiently rapid.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] The equation of hydrostatic equilibrium may need to be modified by adding a radial acceleration term if the radius of the star is changing very quickly, for example if the star is radially pulsating.
[src:stellar-physics/stellar-structure] Also, if the nuclear burning is not stable, or the star's core is rapidly collapsing, an entropy term must be added to the energy equation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A **supernova** (pl.: **supernovae**) is a powerful and luminous explosion of a star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A supernova occurs during the last evolutionary stages of a massive star, or when a white dwarf is triggered into runaway nuclear fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The original object, called the *progenitor*, either collapses to a neutron star or black hole, or is completely destroyed to form a diffuse nebula.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The peak optical luminosity of a supernova can be comparable to that of an entire galaxy before fading over several weeks or months.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] It is expected that supernovae in our galaxy occur on average once every 61 years, although the last to be observed was Kepler's Supernova in 1604.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] SN 1987A occurred in the Large Magellanic Cloud, a satellite galaxy of our galaxy, in 1987.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Several thousand supernovae are typically seen in distant galaxies every year.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Theoretical studies indicate that most supernovae are triggered by one of two basic mechanisms: the sudden re-ignition of nuclear fusion in a white dwarf, or the sudden gravitational collapse of a massive star's core.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernovae can expel several solar masses of material at speeds up to several percent of the speed of light.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] This drives an expanding shock wave into the surrounding interstellar medium, sweeping up an expanding shell of gas and dust observed as a supernova remnant.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernovae are a major source of elements in the interstellar medium from oxygen to rubidium.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The expanding shock waves of supernovae can trigger the formation of new stars.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernovae are a major source of cosmic rays.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] They might also produce gravitational waves.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The first supernovae to be studied by astronomical methods were Tycho's Supernova in 1572 and Kepler's Supernova in 1604, both of which were in the Milky Way and were visible to the naked eye.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Analysis of the historical record suggests that, aside from telescope discoveries, fewer than 10 supernovae have been observed over the last 2,000 years.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Observations of recent supernova remnants within the Milky Way, coupled with studies of supernovae in other galaxies, suggest that these powerful stellar explosions occur in our galaxy approximately 1.6 to 4.6 times per century on average.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] In 1987, the supernova SN 1987A appeared in the Large Magellanic Cloud, a satellite galaxy of the Milky Way in an easily studied part of the sky.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Many astronomical observations were made on SN 1987A, including the only measurements of astronomical neutrinos other than the Sun's.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The event was attributed to an explosion of a blue supergiant star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The word *supernova* has the plural form *supernovae* (/-viː/) or *supernovas* and is often abbreviated as SN or SNe.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] It is derived from the Latin word *nova*, meaning 'new', which refers to what appears to be a temporary new bright star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Adding the prefix "super-" distinguishes supernovae from ordinary novae, which are far less luminous.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The word *supernova* was coined by Walter Baade and Fritz Zwicky, who began using it in astrophysics lectures in 1931.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Its first use in a journal article came the following year in a publication by Knut Lundmark, who may have coined it independently.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Compared to a star's entire history, the visual appearance of a supernova is very brief, sometimes spanning several months, so that the chances of observing one with the naked eye are roughly once in a lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Only a tiny fraction of the 100 billion stars in a typical galaxy have the capacity to become a supernova, the ability being restricted to those having high mass and those in rare kinds of binary star systems with at least one white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A rock carving in the Burzahama region of Kashmir, dated to 4500±1000 BC showing what might be nova HB9 is the earliest of many claimed but unverifiable records of supernovae by prehistoric people.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The first widely recorded supernova was SN 1006, observed in AD 1006 in the constellation of Lupus.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] This event was described by observers in China, Japan, Iraq, Egypt and Europe.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The supernova SN 1054, which produced the Crab Nebula, was recorded by Chinese astronomers in AD 1054.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernovae SN 1572 and SN 1604, the latest Milky Way supernovae to be observed with the naked eye, had a notable influence on the development of astronomy in Europe because they were used to argue against the Aristotelian idea that the universe beyond the Moon and planets was static and unchanging.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Johannes Kepler began observing SN 1604 at its peak on 17 October 1604, and continued to make estimates of its brightness until it faded from naked eye view a year later.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] It was the second supernova to be observed in a generation, after Tycho Brahe observed SN 1572 in Cassiopeia.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] There is some evidence that the youngest known supernova in our galaxy, G1.9+0.3, occurred in the late 19th century, considerably more recently than Cassiopeia A from around 1680.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] In the case of G1.9+0.3, high extinction from dust along the plane of the galactic disk could have dimmed the event sufficiently for it to go unnoticed.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The situation for Cassiopeia A is less clear; infrared light echoes have been detected showing that it was not in a region of especially high extinction.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A 1414 text cites a 1055 report: since "the baleful star appeared, a full year has passed and until now its brilliance has not faded".
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] With the development of the astronomical telescope, observation and discovery of fainter and more distant supernovae became possible.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The first such observation was of SN 1885A in the Andromeda Galaxy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A decade later, two further supernovae, SN 1895A and SN 1895B, were discovered in NGC 4424 and NGC 5253 respectively.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Early work on what was originally believed to be simply a new category of novae was performed during the 1920s.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] These were variously called "upper-class Novae", "Hauptnovae", or "giant novae".
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The name "supernovae" is thought to have been coined by Walter Baade and Fritz Zwicky in lectures at Caltech in 1931.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] It was used, as "super-Novae", in a journal paper published by Knut Lundmark in 1933, and in a 1934 paper by Baade and Zwicky.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] By 1938, the hyphen was no longer used and the modern name was in use.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Rudolph Minkowski and Fritz Zwicky developed the modern supernova classification scheme beginning in 1941.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] During the 1960s, astronomers found that the maximum intensities of supernovae could be used as standard candles, hence indicators of astronomical distances.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Some of the most distant supernovae observed in 2003 appeared dimmer than expected.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] This supports the view that the expansion of the universe is accelerating.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Techniques were developed for reconstructing supernovae events that have no written records of being observed.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The date of the Cassiopeia A supernova event was determined from light echoes off nebulae, while the age of supernova remnant RX J0852.0-4622 was estimated from temperature measurements and the gamma ray emissions from the radioactive decay of 44 Ti.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The most luminous supernova ever recorded is ASASSN-15lh, at a distance of 3.82 gigalight-years.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] It was first detected in June 2015 and peaked at 570 billion *L*☉, which is twice the bolometric luminosity of any other known supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The nature of this supernova is debated and several alternative explanations, such as tidal disruption of a star by a black hole, have been suggested.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] SN 2013fs was recorded three hours after the supernova event on 6 October 2013, by the Intermediate Palomar Transient Factory.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] This is among the earliest supernovae caught after detonation, and it is the earliest for which spectra have been obtained, beginning six hours after the actual explosion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The star is located in a spiral galaxy named NGC 7610, 160 million light-years away in the constellation of Pegasus.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The supernova SN 2016gkg was detected by amateur astronomer Victor Buso from Rosario, Argentina, on 20 September 2016.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] It was the first time that the initial "shock breakout" from an optical supernova had been observed.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The progenitor star has been identified in Hubble Space Telescope images from before its collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Because supernovae are relatively rare events within a galaxy, occurring about three times a century in the Milky Way, obtaining a good sample of supernovae to study requires regular monitoring of many galaxies.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Today, amateur and professional astronomers are finding about two thousand every year, some when near maximum brightness, others on old astronomical photographs or plates.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernovae in other galaxies cannot be predicted with any meaningful accuracy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Normally, when they are discovered, they are already in progress.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] To use supernovae as standard candles for measuring distance, observation of their peak luminosity is required.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] It is therefore important to discover them well before they reach their maximum.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Amateur astronomers, who greatly outnumber professional astronomers, have played an important role in finding supernovae, typically by looking at some of the closer galaxies through an optical telescope and comparing them to earlier photographs.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Toward the end of the 20th century, astronomers increasingly turned to computer-controlled telescopes and CCDs for hunting supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] While such systems are popular with amateurs, there are also professional installations such as the Katzman Automatic Imaging Telescope.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The Supernova Early Warning System (SNEWS) project uses a network of neutrino detectors to give early warning of a supernova in the Milky Way galaxy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Neutrinos are subatomic particles that are produced in great quantities by a supernova, and they are not significantly absorbed by the interstellar gas and dust of the galactic disk.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernova searches fall into two classes: those focused on relatively nearby events and those looking farther away.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Because of the expansion of the universe, the distance to a remote object with a known emission spectrum can be estimated by measuring its Doppler shift (or redshift); on average, more-distant objects recede with greater velocity than those nearby, and so have a higher redshift.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Thus the search is split between high redshift and low redshift, with the boundary falling around a redshift range of z=0.1–0.3, where z is a dimensionless measure of the spectrum's frequency shift.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] High-redshift searches for supernovae usually involve the observation of supernova light curves.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] These are useful for standard or calibrated candles to generate Hubble diagrams and make cosmological predictions.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernova spectroscopy, used to study the physics and environments of supernovae, is more practical at low than at high redshift.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Low redshift observations also anchor the low-distance end of the Hubble curve, which is a plot of distance versus redshift for visible galaxies.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] As survey programmes rapidly increase the number of detected supernovae, collated collections of observations (light decay curves, astrometry, pre-supernova observations, spectroscopy) have been assembled.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The Pantheon data set, assembled in 2018, detailed 1048 supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] In 2021, this data set was expanded to 1701 light curves for 1550 supernovae taken from 18 different surveys, a 50% increase in under 3 years.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernova discoveries are reported to the International Astronomical Union's Central Bureau for Astronomical Telegrams, which sends out a circular with the name it assigns to that supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The name is formed from the prefix *SN*, followed by the year of discovery, suffixed with a one- to four-letter designation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The first 26 supernovae of the year are designated with a capital letter from *A* to *Z*.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Next, pairs of lower-case letters are used: *aa*, *ab*, and so on.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] After zz comes aaa, then aab, aac, and so on.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Hence, for example, SN 2003C designates the third supernova reported in the year 2003.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The last supernova retained in the Asiago Supernova Catalogue when it was terminated on 31 December 2017 bears the designation SN 2017jzp.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] SN 2021afdx is an example of a four-letter suffix.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Historical supernovae are known simply by the year they occurred: SN 185, SN 1006, SN 1054, SN 1572 (called *Tycho's Nova*) and SN 1604 (*Kepler's Star*).
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Since 1885 the additional letter notation has been used, even if there was only one supernova discovered that year (for example, SN 1885A, SN 1907A, etc.); this last happened with SN 1947A.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Until 1987, two-letter designations were rarely needed; since 1988, they have been needed every year.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Since 2000, professional and amateur astronomers have been finding several hundred supernovae each year (572 in 2007, 261 in 2008, 390 in 2009; 231 in 2013).
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Since 2016, the increasing number of discoveries has regularly led to the additional use of three-letter designations.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Astronomers classify supernovae according to their light curves and the absorption lines of different chemical elements that appear in their spectra.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] If a supernova's spectrum contains lines of hydrogen (known as the Balmer series in the visual portion of the spectrum) it is classified *Type II*; otherwise it is *Type I*.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] In each of these two types there are subdivisions according to the presence of lines from other elements or the shape of the light curve (a graph of the supernova's apparent magnitude as a function of time).
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Type I supernovae are subdivided on the basis of their spectra, with Type Ia showing a strong ionised silicon absorption line.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Type I supernovae without this strong line are classified as Type Ib and Ic, with Type Ib showing strong neutral helium lines and Type Ic lacking them.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Historically, the light curves of Type I supernovae were seen as all broadly similar, too much so to make useful distinctions.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] While variations in light curves have been studied, classification continues to be made on spectral grounds rather than light-curve shape.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A small number of Type Ia supernovae exhibit unusual features, such as non-standard luminosity or broadened light curves, and these are typically categorised by referring to the earliest example showing similar features.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] For example, the sub-luminous SN 2008ha is often referred to as SN 2002cx-like or class Ia-2002cx.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A small proportion of Type Ic supernovae show highly broadened and blended emission lines which are taken to indicate very high expansion velocities for the ejecta.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] These have been classified as Type Ic-BL or Ic-bl.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Calcium-rich supernovae are a rare type of very fast supernova with unusually strong calcium lines in their spectra.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Models suggest they occur when material is accreted from a helium-rich companion rather than a hydrogen-rich star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Because of helium lines in their spectra, they can resemble Type Ib supernovae, but are thought to have very different progenitors.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Type Ien has been proposed to explain observations of the supernova SN 2021yfj.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Having lost its outer layers of hydrogen, helium and carbon, the star, just before the explosion, released an unusual, hidden layer of silicon, sulfur and argon, elements that are not often seen in dying stars.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] During the explosion, the material from the star's core collided with the gaseous shell, and the heat of the collision caused the silicon and sulfur layer to glow.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The explosion showed that stars can be completely stripped down and still produce a brilliant explosion observable from very far distance.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The discovery provided direct evidence of the long-theorized, but difficult to observe, internal structure of massive stars.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] In the type's name, "e" describes the position of the silicon/sulfur layer in the internal structure, while "n" signifies narrow emission lines.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The supernovae of Type II can also be sub-divided based on their spectra.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] While most Type II supernovae show very broad emission lines which indicate expansion velocities of many thousands of kilometres per second, some, such as SN 2005gl, have relatively narrow features in their spectra.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] These are called Type IIn, where the "n" stands for "narrow".
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] A few supernovae, such as SN 1987K and SN 1993J, appear to change types: they show lines of hydrogen at early times, but, over a period of weeks to months, become dominated by lines of helium.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The term "Type IIb" is used to describe the combination of features normally associated with Type II and Type Ib.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Type II supernovae with normal spectra dominated by broad hydrogen lines that remain for the life of the decline are classified on the basis of their light curves.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The most common type shows a distinctive "plateau" in the light curve shortly after peak brightness where the visual luminosity stays relatively constant for several months before the decline resumes.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] These are called Type II-P referring to the plateau.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Less common are Type II-L supernovae that lack a distinct plateau.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The "L" signifies "linear" although the light curve is not actually a straight line.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernovae that do not fit into the normal classifications are designated peculiar, or "pec".
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Zwicky defined additional supernovae types based on a very few examples that did not cleanly fit the parameters for Type I or Type II supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] SN 1961i in NGC 4303 was the prototype and only member of the Type III supernova class, noted for its broad light curve maximum and broad hydrogen Balmer lines that were slow to develop in the spectrum.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] SN 1961f in NGC 3003 was the prototype and only member of the Type IV class, with a light curve similar to a Type II-P supernova, with hydrogen absorption lines but weak hydrogen emission lines.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The Type V class was coined for SN 1961V in NGC 1058, an unusual faint supernova or supernova impostor with a slow rise to brightness, a maximum lasting many months, and an unusual emission spectrum.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] The similarity of SN 1961V to the Eta Carinae Great Outburst was noted.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] Supernovae in M101 (1909) and M83 (1923 and 1957) were also suggested as possible Type IV or Type V supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p01] These types would now all be treated as peculiar Type II supernovae (IIpec), of which many more examples have been discovered, although it is still debated whether SN 1961V was a true supernova following an LBV outburst or an impostor.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Supernova type codes, as summarised in the table above, are *taxonomic*: the type number is based on the light observed from the supernova, not necessarily its cause.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] For example, Type Ia supernovae are produced by runaway fusion ignited on degenerate white dwarf progenitors, while the spectrally similar Type Ib/c are produced from massive stripped progenitor stars by core collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] A white dwarf star may accumulate sufficient material from a stellar companion to raise its core temperature enough to ignite carbon fusion, at which point it undergoes runaway nuclear fusion, completely disrupting it.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] There are three avenues by which this detonation is theorised to happen: stable accretion of material from a companion, the collision of two white dwarfs, or accretion that causes ignition in a shell that then ignites the core.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The dominant mechanism by which Type Ia supernovae are produced remains unclear.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Despite this uncertainty in how Type Ia supernovae are produced, Type Ia supernovae have very uniform properties and are useful standard candles over intergalactic distances.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Some calibrations are required to compensate for the gradual change in properties or different frequencies of abnormal luminosity supernovae at high redshift, and for small variations in brightness identified by light curve shape or spectrum.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] There are several means by which a supernova of this type can form, but they share a common underlying mechanism.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] If a carbon-oxygen white dwarf accreted enough matter to reach the Chandrasekhar limit of about 1.44 solar masses (for a non-rotating star), then it would no longer be able to support the bulk of its mass through electron degeneracy pressure and would begin to collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] However, the current view is that this limit is not normally attained; increasing temperature and density inside the core ignite carbon fusion as the star approaches the limit (to within about 1%) before collapse is initiated.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In contrast, for a core primarily composed of oxygen, neon and magnesium, the collapsing white dwarf will typically form a neutron star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In this case, only a fraction of the star's mass will be ejected during the collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Within a few seconds of the collapse process, a substantial fraction of the matter in the white dwarf undergoes nuclear fusion, releasing enough energy (1–2×1044 J) to unbind the star in a supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] An outwardly expanding shock wave is generated, with matter reaching velocities on the order of 5,000–20,000 km/s, or roughly 3% of the speed of light.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] There is also a significant increase in luminosity, reaching an absolute magnitude of −19.3 (or 5 billion times brighter than the Sun), with little variation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The model for the formation of this category of supernova is a close binary star system.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The more massive of the two stars is the first to evolve off the main sequence, and it expands to form a red giant.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The two stars now share a common envelope, causing their mutual orbit to shrink.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The giant star then sheds most of its envelope, losing mass until it can no longer continue nuclear fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] At this point, it becomes a white dwarf star, composed primarily of carbon and oxygen.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Eventually, the secondary star also evolves off the main sequence to form a red giant.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Matter from the giant is accreted by the white dwarf, causing the latter to increase in mass.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The exact details of initiation and of the heavy elements produced in the catastrophic event remain unclear.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ia supernovae produce a characteristic light curve—the graph of luminosity as a function of time—after the event.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This luminosity is generated by the radioactive decay of 56 Ni through 56 Co to 56 Fe.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The peak luminosity of the light curve is extremely consistent across normal Type Ia supernovae, having a maximum absolute magnitude of about −19.3.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This is because typical Type Ia supernovae arise from a consistent type of progenitor star by gradual mass acquisition, and explode when they acquire a consistent typical mass, giving rise to very similar supernova conditions and behaviour.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This allows them to be used as a secondary standard candle to measure the distance to their host galaxies.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] A second model for the formation of Type Ia supernovae involves the merger of two white dwarf stars, with the combined mass momentarily exceeding the Chandrasekhar limit.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This is sometimes referred to as the double-degenerate model, as both stars are degenerate white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Due to the possible combinations of mass and chemical composition of the pair there is much variation in this type of event, and, in many cases, there may be no supernova at all, in which case they will have a less luminous light curve than the more normal SN Type Ia.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Abnormally bright Type Ia supernovae occur when the white dwarf already has a mass higher than the Chandrasekhar limit, possibly enhanced further by asymmetry, but the ejected material will have less than normal kinetic energy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This super-Chandrasekhar-mass scenario can occur, for example, when the extra mass is supported by differential rotation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] There is no formal sub-classification for non-standard Type Ia supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] It has been proposed that a group of sub-luminous supernovae that occur when helium accretes onto a white dwarf should be classified as **Type Iax**.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This type of supernova may not always completely destroy the white dwarf progenitor and could leave behind a zombie star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] One specific type of supernova originates from exploding white dwarfs, like Type Ia, but contains hydrogen lines in their spectra, possibly because the white dwarf is surrounded by an envelope of hydrogen-rich circumstellar material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These supernovae have been dubbed **Type Ia/IIn**, **Type Ian**, **Type IIa** and **Type IIan**.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The quadruple star HD 74438, belonging to the open cluster IC 2391 the Vela constellation, has been predicted to become a non-standard Type Ia supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Very massive stars can undergo core collapse when nuclear fusion becomes unable to sustain the core against its own gravity; passing this threshold is the cause of all types of supernova except Type Ia.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The collapse may cause violent expulsion of the outer layers of the star resulting in a supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] However, if the release of gravitational potential energy is insufficient, the star may instead collapse into a black hole or neutron star with little radiated energy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Core collapse can be caused by several different mechanisms: exceeding the Chandrasekhar limit; electron capture; pair-instability; or photodisintegration.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The table below lists the known reasons for core collapse in massive stars, the types of stars in which they occur, their associated supernova type, and the remnant produced.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The metallicity is the proportion of elements other than hydrogen or helium, as compared to the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The initial mass is the mass of the star prior to the supernova event, given in multiples of the Sun's mass, although the mass at the time of the supernova may be much lower.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type IIn supernovae are not listed in the table.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] They can be produced by various types of core collapse in different progenitor stars, possibly even by Type Ia white dwarf ignitions, although it seems that most will be from iron core collapse in luminous supergiants or hypergiants (including LBVs).
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The narrow spectral lines for which they are named occur because the supernova is expanding into a small dense cloud of circumstellar material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] It appears that a significant proportion of supposed Type IIn supernovae are supernova impostors, massive eruptions of LBV-like stars similar to the Great Eruption of Eta Carinae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In these events, material previously ejected from the star creates the narrow absorption lines and causes a shock wave through interaction with the newly ejected material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] When a stellar core is no longer supported against gravity, it collapses in on itself with velocities reaching 70,000 km/s (0.23*c*), resulting in a rapid increase in temperature and density.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] What follows depends on the mass and structure of the collapsing core, with low-mass degenerate cores forming neutron stars, higher-mass degenerate cores mostly collapsing completely to black holes, and non-degenerate cores undergoing runaway fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The initial collapse of degenerate cores is accelerated by beta decay, photodisintegration and electron capture, which causes a burst of electron neutrinos.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] As the density increases, neutrino emission is cut off as they become trapped in the core.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The inner core eventually reaches typically 30 km in diameter with a density comparable to that of an atomic nucleus, and neutron degeneracy pressure tries to halt the collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] If the core mass is more than about 15 solar masses then neutron degeneracy is insufficient to stop the collapse and a black hole forms directly with no supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In lower mass cores the collapse is stopped and the newly formed neutron core has an initial temperature of about 100 billion kelvins, 6,000 times the temperature of the Sun's core.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] At this temperature, neutrino-antineutrino pairs of all flavours are efficiently formed by thermal emission.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These thermal neutrinos are several times more abundant than the electron-capture neutrinos.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] About 1046 joules, approximately 10% of the star's rest mass, is converted into a ten-second burst of neutrinos, which is the main output of the event.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The suddenly halted core collapse rebounds and produces a shock wave that stalls in the outer core within milliseconds as energy is lost through the dissociation of heavy elements.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] A process that is not clearly understood is necessary to allow the outer layers of the core to reabsorb around 1044 joules (1 foe) from the neutrino pulse, producing the visible brightness, although there are other theories that could power the explosion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Some material from the outer envelope falls back onto the neutron star, and, for cores beyond about 8 *M*☉, there is sufficient fallback to form a black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This fallback will reduce the kinetic energy created and the mass of expelled radioactive material, but in some situations, it may also generate relativistic jets that result in a gamma-ray burst or an exceptionally luminous supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The collapse of a massive non-degenerate core will ignite further fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] When the core collapse is initiated by pair instability (photons turning into electron-positron pairs, thereby reducing the radiation pressure) oxygen fusion begins and the collapse may be halted.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] For core masses of 40–60 *M*☉, the collapse halts and the star remains intact, but collapse will occur again when a larger core has formed.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] For cores of around 60–130 *M*☉, the fusion of oxygen and heavier elements is so energetic that the entire star is disrupted, causing a supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] At the upper end of the mass range, the supernova is unusually luminous and extremely long-lived due to many solar masses of ejected 56 Ni.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] For even larger core masses, the core temperature becomes high enough to allow photodisintegration and the core collapses completely into a black hole.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Stars with initial masses less than about 8 *M*☉ never develop a core large enough to collapse and they eventually lose their atmospheres to become white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Stars with at least 9 *M*☉ (possibly as much as 12 *M*☉) evolve in a complex fashion, progressively burning heavier elements at hotter temperatures in their cores.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The star becomes layered like an onion, with the burning of more easily fused elements occurring in larger shells.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Although popularly described as an onion with an iron core, the least massive supernova progenitors only have oxygen-neon(-magnesium) cores.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These super-AGB stars may form the majority of core collapse supernovae, although less luminous and so less commonly observed than those from more massive progenitors.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] If core collapse occurs during a supergiant phase when the star still has a hydrogen envelope, the result is a Type II supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The rate of mass loss for luminous stars depends on the metallicity and luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Extremely luminous stars at near solar metallicity will lose all their hydrogen before they reach core collapse and so will not form a supernova of Type II.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] At low metallicity, all stars will reach core collapse with a hydrogen envelope but sufficiently massive stars collapse directly to a black hole without producing a visible supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Stars with an initial mass up to about 90 times the Sun, or a little less at high metallicity, result in a Type II-P supernova, which is the most commonly observed type.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] At moderate to high metallicity, stars near the upper end of that mass range will have lost most of their hydrogen when core collapse occurs and the result will be a Type II-L supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] At very low metallicity, stars of around 140–250 *M*☉ will reach core collapse by pair instability while they still have a hydrogen atmosphere and an oxygen core and the result will be a supernova with Type II characteristics but a very large mass of ejected 56 Ni and high luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These supernovae, like those of Type II, are massive stars that undergo core collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Unlike the progenitors of Type II supernovae, the stars which become Type Ib and Type Ic supernovae have lost most of their outer (hydrogen) envelopes due to strong stellar winds or else from interaction with a companion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These stars are known as Wolf–Rayet stars, and they occur at moderate to high metallicity where continuum driven winds cause sufficiently high mass-loss rates.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Observations of Type Ib/c supernova do not match the observed or expected occurrence of Wolf–Rayet stars.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Alternate explanations for this type of core collapse supernova involve stars stripped of their hydrogen by binary interactions.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Binary models provide a better match for the observed supernovae, with the proviso that no suitable binary helium stars have ever been observed.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ib supernovae are more common than Type Ic and they result from Wolf–Rayet stars of type WC which still have helium in their atmospheres.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] For a narrow range of masses, stars evolve further before reaching core collapse to become WO stars with very little helium remaining, and these are the progenitors of Type Ic supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] A few percent of the Type Ic supernovae are associated with gamma-ray bursts (GRB), though it is also believed that any hydrogen-stripped Type Ib or Ic supernova could produce a GRB, depending on the circumstances of the geometry.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The mechanism for producing this type of GRB is the jets produced by the magnetic field of the rapidly spinning magnetar formed at the collapsing core of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The jets would also transfer energy into the expanding outer shell, producing a super-luminous supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Ultra-stripped supernovae occur when the exploding star has been stripped (almost) all the way to the metal core, via mass transfer in a close binary.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] As a result, very little material is ejected from the exploding star (c.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In the most extreme cases, ultra-stripped supernovae can occur in naked metal cores, barely above the Chandrasekhar mass limit.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] SN 2005ek might be the first observational example of an ultra-stripped supernova, giving rise to a relatively dim and fast decaying light curve.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The nature of ultra-stripped supernovae can be both iron core-collapse and electron capture supernovae, depending on the mass of the collapsing core.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Ultra-stripped supernovae are believed to be associated with the second supernova explosion in a binary system, producing for example a tight double neutron star system.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In 2022 a team of astronomers led by researchers from the Weizmann Institute of Science reported the first supernova explosion showing direct evidence for a Wolf-Rayet progenitor star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] SN 2019hgp was a Type Icn supernova and is also the first in which the element neon has been detected.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In 1980, a "third type" of supernova was predicted by Ken'ichi Nomoto of the University of Tokyo, called an electron-capture supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In June 2021, a paper in the journal *Nature Astronomy* reported that the 2018 supernova SN 2018zd (in the galaxy NGC 2146, about 31 million light-years from Earth) appeared to be the first observation of an electron-capture supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The 1054 supernova explosion that created the Crab Nebula in our galaxy had been thought to be the best candidate for an electron-capture supernova, and the 2021 paper makes it more likely that this was correct.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The core collapse of some massive stars may not result in a visible supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This happens if the initial core collapse cannot be reversed by the mechanism that produces an explosion, usually because the core is too massive.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These events are difficult to detect, but large surveys have detected possible candidates.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The red supergiant N6946-BH1 in NGC 6946 underwent a modest outburst in March 2009, before fading from view.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Only a faint infrared source remains at the star's location.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The gases ejected by a supernova would dim quickly without some energy input to keep them hot.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The source of this energy—which can maintain the optical supernova glow for months—was, at first, a puzzle.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Some considered rotational energy from the central pulsar as a source.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Although the energy that initially powers each type of supernovae is delivered promptly, the light curves are dominated by subsequent radioactive heating of the rapidly expanding ejecta.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The intensely radioactive nature of the ejecta gases was first calculated on sound nucleosynthesis grounds in the late 1960s, and this has since been demonstrated as correct for most supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] It was not until SN 1987A that direct observation of gamma-ray lines unambiguously identified the major radioactive nuclei.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] It is now known by direct observation that much of the light curve (the graph of luminosity as a function of time) after the occurrence of a Type II Supernova, such as SN 1987A, is explained by those predicted radioactive decays.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Although the luminous emission consists of optical photons, it is the radioactive power absorbed by the ejected gases that keeps the remnant hot enough to radiate light.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The radioactive decay of 56 Ni through its daughters 56 Co to 56 Fe produces gamma-ray photons, primarily with energies of 847 keV and 1,238 keV, that are absorbed and dominate the heating and thus the luminosity of the ejecta at intermediate times (several weeks) to late times (several months).
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Energy for the peak of the light curve of SN1987A was provided by the decay of 56 Ni to 56 Co (half-life 6 days) while energy for the later light curve in particular fit very closely with the 77.3-day half-life of 56 Co decaying to 56 Fe.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Later measurements by space gamma-ray telescopes of the small fraction of the 56 Co and 57 Co gamma rays that escaped the SN 1987A remnant without absorption confirmed earlier predictions that those two radioactive nuclei were the power sources.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The light curves can be significantly different at other wavelengths.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] For example, at ultraviolet wavelengths there is an early extremely luminous peak lasting only a few hours corresponding to the breakout of the shock launched by the initial event, but that breakout is hardly detectable optically.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The light curves for Type Ia are mostly very uniform, with a consistent maximum absolute magnitude and a relatively steep decline in luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Their optical energy output is driven by radioactive decay of ejected 56 Ni (half-life 6 days), which then decays to radioactive 56 Co (half-life 77 days).
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These radioisotopes excite the surrounding material to incandescence.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Modern studies of cosmology rely on 56 Ni radioactivity providing the energy for the optical brightness of supernovae of Type Ia, which are the "standard candles" of cosmology but whose diagnostic 847 keV and 1,238 keV gamma rays were first detected only in 2014.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The initial phases of the light curve decline steeply as the effective size of the photosphere decreases and trapped electromagnetic radiation is depleted.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] After several months, the light curve changes its decline rate again as positron emission from the remaining 56 Co becomes dominant, although this portion of the light curve has been little-studied.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ib and Ic light curves are similar to Type Ia although with a lower average peak luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The visual light output is again due to radioactive decay being converted into visual radiation, but there is a much lower mass of the created 56 Ni.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The peak luminosity varies considerably and there are even occasional Type Ib/c supernovae orders of magnitude more and less luminous than the norm.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The most luminous Type Ic supernovae are referred to as hypernovae and tend to have broadened light curves in addition to the increased peak luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The source of the extra energy is thought to be relativistic jets driven by the formation of a rotating black hole, which also produce gamma-ray bursts.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The light curves for Type II supernovae are characterised by a much slower decline than Type I, on the order of 0.05 magnitudes per day, excluding the plateau phase.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The visual light output is dominated by kinetic energy rather than radioactive decay for several months, due primarily to the existence of hydrogen in the ejecta from the atmosphere of the supergiant progenitor star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In the initial destruction this hydrogen becomes heated and ionised.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The majority of Type II supernovae show a prolonged plateau in their light curves as this hydrogen recombines, emitting visible light and becoming more transparent.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This is then followed by a declining light curve driven by radioactive decay although slower than in Type I supernovae, due to the efficiency of conversion into light by all the hydrogen.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In Type II-L the plateau is absent because the progenitor had relatively little hydrogen left in its atmosphere, sufficient to appear in the spectrum but insufficient to produce a noticeable plateau in the light output.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In Type IIb supernovae the hydrogen atmosphere of the progenitor is so depleted (thought to be due to tidal stripping by a companion star) that the light curve is closer to a Type I supernova and the hydrogen even disappears from the spectrum after several weeks.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type IIn supernovae are characterised by additional narrow spectral lines produced in a dense shell of circumstellar material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Their light curves are generally very broad and extended, occasionally also extremely luminous and referred to as a superluminous supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These light curves are produced by the highly efficient conversion of kinetic energy of the ejecta into electromagnetic radiation by interaction with the dense shell of material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This only occurs when the material is sufficiently dense and compact, indicating that it has been produced by the progenitor star itself only shortly before the supernova occurs.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Large numbers of supernovae have been catalogued and classified to provide distance candles and test models.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Average characteristics vary somewhat with distance and type of host galaxy, but can broadly be specified for each supernova type.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] **^**These magnitudes are measured in the R band.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Measurements in V or B bands are common and will be around half a magnitude brighter for supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Total electromagnetic radiated energy is usually lower, (theoretical) neutrino energy much higher.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] **^**Probably a heterogeneous group, any of the other types embedded in nebulosity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The initial impetus can be substantial, propelling an object of more than a solar mass at a velocity of 500 km/s or greater.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This indicates an expansion asymmetry, but the mechanism by which momentum is transferred to the compact object remains a puzzle.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Proposed explanations for this kick include convection in the collapsing star, asymmetric ejection of matter during neutron star formation, and asymmetrical neutrino emissions.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] One possible explanation for this asymmetry is large-scale convection above the core.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The convection can create radial variations in density giving rise to variations in the amount of energy absorbed from neutrino outflow.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] However analysis of this mechanism predicts only modest momentum transfer.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Another possible explanation is that accretion of gas onto the central neutron star can create a disk that drives highly directional jets, propelling matter at a high velocity out of the star, and driving transverse shocks that completely disrupt the star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These jets might play a crucial role in the resulting supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] (A similar model is used for explaining long gamma-ray bursts.) The dominant mechanism may depend upon the mass of the progenitor star.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Initial asymmetries have also been confirmed in Type Ia supernovae through observation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This result may mean that the initial luminosity of this type of supernova depends on the viewing angle.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] However, the expansion becomes more symmetrical with the passage of time.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Early asymmetries are detectable by measuring the polarisation of the emitted light.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Although supernovae are primarily known as luminous events, the electromagnetic radiation they release is almost a minor side-effect.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Particularly in the case of core collapse supernovae, the emitted electromagnetic radiation is a tiny fraction of the total energy released during the event.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] There is a fundamental difference between the balance of energy production in the different types of supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In Type Ia white dwarf detonations, most of the energy is directed into heavy element synthesis and the kinetic energy of the ejecta.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In core collapse supernovae, the vast majority of the energy is directed into neutrino emission, and while some of this apparently powers the observed destruction, 99%+ of the neutrinos escape the star in the first few minutes following the start of the collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Standard Type Ia supernovae derive their energy from a runaway nuclear fusion of a carbon-oxygen white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The details of the energetics are still not fully understood, but the result is the ejection of the entire mass of the original star at high kinetic energy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Around half a solar mass of that mass is 56 Ni generated from silicon burning.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] 56 Ni is radioactive and decays into 56 Co by beta plus decay (with a half life of six days) and gamma rays.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] 56 Co itself decays by the beta plus (positron) path with a half-life of 77 days into stable 56 Fe.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These two processes are responsible for the electromagnetic radiation from Type Ia supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In combination with the changing transparency of the ejected material, they produce the rapidly declining light curve.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Core collapse supernovae are on average visually fainter than Type Ia supernovae, but the total energy released is far higher, as outlined in the following table.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In some core collapse supernovae, fallback onto a black hole drives relativistic jets which may produce a brief energetic and directional burst of gamma rays and also transfers substantial further energy into the ejected material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This is one scenario for producing high-luminosity supernovae and is thought to be the cause of Type Ic hypernovae and long-duration gamma-ray bursts.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] If the relativistic jets are too brief and fail to penetrate the stellar envelope then a low-luminosity gamma-ray burst may be produced and the supernova may be sub-luminous.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] When a supernova occurs inside a small dense cloud of circumstellar material, it will produce a shock wave that can efficiently convert a high fraction of the kinetic energy into electromagnetic radiation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Even though the initial energy was entirely normal the resulting supernova will have high luminosity and extended duration since it does not rely on exponential radioactive decay.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This type of event may cause Type IIn hypernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Although pair-instability supernovae are core collapse supernovae with spectra and light curves similar to Type II-P, the nature after core collapse is more like that of a giant Type Ia with runaway fusion of carbon, oxygen and silicon.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The total energy released by the highest-mass events is comparable to other core collapse supernovae but neutrino production is thought to be very low, hence the kinetic and electromagnetic energy released is very high.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The cores of these stars are much larger than any white dwarf and the amount of radioactive nickel and other heavy elements ejected from their cores can be orders of magnitude higher, with consequently high visual luminosity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The supernova classification type is closely tied to the type of progenitor star at the time of the collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The occurrence of each type of supernova depends on the star's metallicity, since this affects the strength of the stellar wind and thereby the rate at which the star loses mass.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ia supernovae are produced from white dwarf stars in binary star systems and occur in all galaxy types.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Core collapse supernovae are only found in galaxies undergoing current or very recent star formation, since they result from short-lived massive stars.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] They are most commonly found in type Sc spirals, but also in the arms of other spiral galaxies and in irregular galaxies, especially starburst galaxies.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ib and Ic supernovae are hypothesised to have been produced by core collapse of massive stars that have lost their outer layer of hydrogen and helium, either via strong stellar winds or mass transfer to a companion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] They normally occur in regions of new star formation, and are extremely rare in elliptical galaxies.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The progenitors of Type IIn supernovae also have high rates of mass loss in the period just prior to their explosions.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ic supernovae have been observed to occur in regions that are more metal-rich and have higher star-formation rates than average for their host galaxies.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The table shows the progenitor for the main types of core collapse supernova, and the approximate proportions that have been observed in the local neighbourhood.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] There are a number of difficulties reconciling modelled and observed stellar evolution leading up to core collapse supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Red supergiants are the progenitors for the vast majority of core collapse supernovae, and these have been observed but only at relatively low masses and luminosities, below about 18 *M*☉ and 100,000 *L*☉, respectively.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Most progenitors of Type II supernovae are not detected and must be considerably fainter, and presumably less massive.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This discrepancy has been referred to as the **red supergiant problem**.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] It was first described in 2009 by Stephen Smartt, who also coined the term.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] After performing a volume-limited search for supernovae, Smartt et al. found the lower and upper mass limits for Type II-P supernovae to form to be 8.5+1 −1.5 *M*☉ and 16.5±1.5 *M*☉, respectively.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The former is consistent with the expected upper mass limits for white dwarf progenitors to form, but the latter is not consistent with massive star populations in the Local Group.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The upper limit for red supergiants that produce a visible supernova explosion has been calculated at 19+4 −2 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] It is thought that higher mass red supergiants do not explode as supernovae, but instead evolve back towards hotter temperatures.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Several progenitors of Type IIb supernovae have been confirmed, and these were K and G supergiants, plus one A supergiant.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Yellow hypergiants or LBVs are proposed progenitors for Type IIb supernovae, and almost all Type IIb supernovae near enough to observe have shown such progenitors.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Blue supergiants form an unexpectedly high proportion of confirmed supernova progenitors, partly due to their high luminosity and easy detection, while not a single Wolf–Rayet progenitor has yet been clearly identified.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Models have had difficulty showing how blue supergiants lose enough mass to reach supernova without progressing to a different evolutionary stage.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] One study has shown a possible route for low-luminosity post-red supergiant luminous blue variables to collapse, most likely as a Type IIn supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The progenitors of Type Ib/c supernovae are not observed at all, and constraints on their possible luminosity are often lower than those of known WC stars.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] WO stars are extremely rare and visually relatively faint, so it is difficult to say whether such progenitors are missing or just yet to be observed.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Very luminous progenitors have not been securely identified, despite numerous supernovae being observed near enough that such progenitors would have been clearly imaged.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Population modelling shows that the observed Type Ib/c supernovae could be reproduced by a mixture of single massive stars and stripped-envelope stars from interacting binary systems.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The continued lack of unambiguous detection of progenitors for normal Type Ib and Ic supernovae may be due to most massive stars collapsing directly to a black hole without a supernova outburst.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Most of these supernovae are then produced from lower-mass low-luminosity helium stars in binary systems.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] A small number would be from rapidly rotating massive stars, likely corresponding to the highly energetic Type Ic-BL events that are associated with long-duration gamma-ray bursts.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Supernovae events generate heavier elements that are scattered throughout the surrounding interstellar medium.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The expanding shock wave from a supernova can trigger star formation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Galactic cosmic rays are generated by supernova explosions.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Supernovae are a major source of elements in the interstellar medium from oxygen through to rubidium, though the theoretical abundances of the elements produced or seen in the spectra varies significantly depending on the various supernova types.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ia supernovae produce mainly silicon and iron-peak elements, metals such as nickel and iron.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Core collapse supernovae eject much smaller quantities of the iron-peak elements than Type Ia supernovae, but larger masses of light alpha elements such as oxygen and neon, and elements heavier than zinc.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The latter is especially true with electron capture supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The bulk of the material ejected by Type II supernovae is hydrogen and helium.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The r-process produces highly unstable nuclei that are rich in neutrons and that rapidly beta decay into more stable forms.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In supernovae, r-process reactions are responsible for about half of all the isotopes of elements beyond iron, although neutron star mergers may be the main astrophysical source for many of these elements.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In the modern universe, old asymptotic giant branch (AGB) stars are the dominant source of dust from oxides, carbon and s-process elements.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] However, in the early universe, before AGB stars formed, supernovae may have been the main source of dust.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Remnants of many supernovae consist of a compact object and a rapidly expanding shock wave of material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] This cloud of material sweeps up surrounding interstellar medium during a free expansion phase, which can last for up to two centuries.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The wave then gradually undergoes a period of adiabatic expansion, and will slowly cool and mix with the surrounding interstellar medium over a period of about 10,000 years.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The Big Bang produced hydrogen, helium and traces of lithium, while all heavier elements are synthesised in stars, supernovae, and collisions between neutron stars (thus being indirectly due to supernovae).
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Supernovae tend to enrich the surrounding interstellar medium with elements other than hydrogen and helium, which usually astronomers refer to as "metals".
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These ejected elements ultimately enrich the molecular clouds that are the sites of star formation.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Thus, each stellar generation has a slightly different composition, going from an almost pure mixture of hydrogen and helium to a more metal-rich composition.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Supernovae are the dominant mechanism for distributing these heavier elements, which are formed in a star during its period of nuclear fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The different abundances of elements in the material that forms a star have important influences on the star's life, and may influence the possibility of having planets orbiting it: more giant planets form around stars of higher metallicity.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The kinetic energy of an expanding supernova remnant can trigger star formation by compressing nearby, dense molecular clouds in space.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The increase in turbulent pressure can also prevent star formation if the cloud is unable to lose the excess energy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Evidence from daughter products of short-lived radioactive isotopes shows that a nearby supernova helped determine the composition of the Solar System 4.5 billion years ago, and may even have triggered the formation of this system.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Fast radio bursts (FRBs) are intense, transient pulses of radio waves that typically last no more than milliseconds.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Many explanations for these events have been proposed; magnetars produced by core-collapse supernovae are leading candidates.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Supernova remnants are thought to accelerate a large fraction of galactic primary cosmic rays, but direct evidence for cosmic ray production has only been found in a small number of remnants.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Gamma rays from pion-decay have been detected from the supernova remnants IC 443 and W44.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] These are produced when accelerated protons from the remnant impact on interstellar material.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Supernovae are potentially strong galactic sources of gravitational waves, but none have so far been detected.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The only gravitational wave events so far detected are from mergers of black holes and neutron stars, probable remnants of supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Like the neutrino emissions, the gravitational waves produced by a core-collapse supernova are expected to arrive before the light generated by the subsequent explosion.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Consequently, they may provide information about the core-collapse process that is unavailable by other means.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Most gravitational-wave signals predicted by supernova models are short in duration, lasting less than a second, and thus difficult to detect.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Using the arrival of a neutrino signal may provide a trigger that can identify the time window in which to seek the gravitational wave, helping to distinguish the latter from background noise.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] A near-Earth supernova is a supernova close enough to the Earth to have noticeable effects on its biosphere.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Depending upon the type and energy of the supernova, it could be as far as 3,000 light-years away.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In 1996 it was theorised that traces of past supernovae might be detectable on Earth in the form of metal isotope signatures in rock strata.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Iron-60 enrichment was later reported in deep-sea rock of the Pacific Ocean.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] In 2009, elevated levels of nitrate ions were found in Antarctic ice, which coincided with the 1006 and 1054 supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Gamma rays from these supernovae could have boosted atmospheric levels of nitrogen oxides, which became trapped in the ice.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Historically, nearby supernovae may have influenced the biodiversity of life on the planet.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Geological records suggest that nearby supernova events have led to an increase in cosmic rays, which in turn produced a cooler climate.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] A greater temperature difference between the poles and the equator created stronger winds, increased ocean mixing, and resulted in the transport of nutrients to shallow waters along the continental shelves.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Type Ia supernovae are thought to be potentially the most dangerous if they occur close enough to the Earth.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] Because these supernovae arise from dim, common white dwarf stars in binary systems, it is likely that a supernova that can affect the Earth will occur unpredictably and in a star system that is not well studied.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] The closest-known candidate is IK Pegasi (HR 8210), about 150 light-years away, but observations suggest that it could be as long as 1.9 billion years before the white dwarf can accrete the critical mass required to become a Type Ia supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p02] According to a 2003 estimate, a Type II supernova would have to be closer than 8 parsecs (26 light-years) to destroy half of the Earth's ozone layer, and there are no such candidates closer than about 500 light-years.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] The next supernova in the Milky Way will likely be detectable even if it occurs on the far side of the galaxy.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] It is likely to be produced by the collapse of an unremarkable red supergiant, and it is very probable that it will already have been catalogued in infrared surveys such as 2MASS.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] There is a smaller chance that the next core collapse supernova will be produced by a different type of massive star such as a yellow hypergiant, luminous blue variable, or Wolf–Rayet.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] The chances of the next supernova being a Type Ia produced by a white dwarf are calculated to be about a third of those for a core collapse supernova.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] Again it should be observable wherever it occurs, but it is less likely that the progenitor will ever have been observed.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] It is not even known exactly what a Type Ia progenitor system looks like, and it is difficult to detect them beyond a few parsecs.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] The total supernova rate in the Milky Way is estimated to be between 2 and 12 per century, although one has not actually been observed for several centuries.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] Statistically, the most common variety of core-collapse supernova is Type II-P, and the progenitors of this type are red supergiants.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] It is difficult to identify which of those supergiants are in the final stages of heavy element fusion in their cores and which have millions of years left.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] The most-massive red supergiants shed their atmospheres and evolve to Wolf–Rayet stars before their cores collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] All Wolf–Rayet stars end their lives from the Wolf–Rayet phase within a million years or so, but again it is difficult to identify those that are closest to core collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] One class that is expected to have no more than a few thousand years before exploding are the WO Wolf–Rayet stars, which are known to have exhausted their core helium.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] Only eight of them are known, and only four of those are in the Milky Way.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] Mimosa, Acrux and Hadar or Beta Centauri, three bright star systems in the southern constellation of Crux and Centaurus respectively, each contain blue stars with sufficient masses to explode as supernovae.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] Others have gained notoriety as possible, although not very likely, progenitors for a gamma-ray burst; for example WR 104.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] Identification of candidates for a Type Ia supernova is much more speculative.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] Any binary with an accreting white dwarf might produce a supernova, although the exact mechanism and timescale is still debated.
[src:stellar-physics/supernova-p03] These systems are faint and difficult to identify, but the novae and recurrent novae are such systems that conveniently advertise themselves.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A **white dwarf** is a very dense type of star: in an Earth-sized volume, it packs a mass that is comparable to the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A white dwarf radiates light from residual heat and eventual crystallization, not from nuclear fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Stars like the Sun, whose mass is not high enough to collapse into a neutron star or black hole, are expected to become white dwarf stars later in their evolution.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The nearest known white dwarf is Sirius B, at 8.6 light years, the smaller component of the Sirius binary star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In 1910, Henry Norris Russell, Edward Charles Pickering and Williamina Fleming discovered that, despite being a dim star, 40 Eridani B was of spectral type A, or white.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This would become known as the first white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The name *white dwarf* was coined by Willem Jacob Luyten in 1922.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In 1931 Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar developed a physical model of white dwarfs and he won the 1983 Nobel Prize in Physics for studies in the evolution of stars.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] These compact stars are composed mostly of a highly compressed form of matter.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The composition of the white dwarf produced will depend on the initial mass of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Once formed, the material in a white dwarf no longer undergoes fusion reactions and thus lacks a heat source to support it against gravitational collapse.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Instead, it is supported only by electron degeneracy pressure, causing it to be extremely dense.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The physics of degeneracy yields a maximum mass for a non-rotating white dwarf, the Chandrasekhar limit— approximately 1.44 times the mass of the Sun— beyond which electron degeneracy pressure cannot support it.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Observed white dwarf masses are largely between 0.5 and 0.7 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A white dwarf, very hot when it forms, gradually cools as it radiates its energy.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This radiation, which initially has a high color temperature, lessens and reddens over time.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Eventually, a white dwarf will cool enough that its material will begin to crystallize, but they are expected to exist for 1038 years.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The first white dwarf discovered was in the triple star system of 40 Eridani, which contains the relatively bright main sequence star 40 Eridani A, orbited at a distance by the closer binary system of the white dwarf 40 Eridani B and the main sequence red dwarf 40 Eridani C.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The pair 40 Eridani B/C was discovered by William Herschel on 31 January 1783.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This star was far out of the normal pattern when Russell first created his now famous luminosity (brightness) versus spectral type (color) diagram.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Publicly Russell suggested that the spectral type may not be correct.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] However the spectral type of 40 Eridani B was independently confirmed in 1914 by Walter Adams.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In 1939, Russell looked back on the discovery and noted that Pickering had suggested that such exceptions lead to breakthroughs and in this case it led to the discovery of white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The white dwarf companion of Sirius, Sirius B, was next to be discovered.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] During the nineteenth century, positional measurements of some stars became precise enough to measure small changes in their location.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Friedrich Bessel used position measurements to determine that the stars Sirius (α Canis Majoris) and Procyon (α Canis Minoris) were changing their positions periodically.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In 1844 he predicted that both stars had unseen companions.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Bessel roughly estimated the period of the companion of Sirius to be about half a century; C.A.F.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Peters computed an orbit for it in 1851.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] It was not until 31 January 1862 that Alvan Graham Clark observed a previously unseen star close to Sirius, later identified as the predicted companion.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Adams announced in 1915 that he had found the spectrum of Sirius B to be similar to that of Sirius.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In 1917, Adriaan van Maanen discovered van Maanen's Star, an isolated white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] These three white dwarfs, the first discovered, are the so-called *classical white dwarfs*.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In 1922, Willem Luyten published a series of three papers on faint white stars that had high proper motion, meaning they were low-luminosity white stars close to the Earth.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In his third paper he used the term *dwarf*; the term was later popularized by Arthur Eddington as *white dwarf*.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Eighteen white dwarfs had been discovered by 1939.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Luyten and others continued to search for white dwarfs in the 1940s.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] By 1950, over a hundred were known, and by 1999, over 2000 were known.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Since then the Sloan Digital Sky Survey has found over 9000 white dwarfs, mostly new.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The extreme density of white dwarf stars was initially a theoretical puzzle.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] If a star is in a binary system, as is the case for Sirius B or 40 Eridani B, it is possible to estimate its mass from observations of the binary orbit.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This was done for Sirius B by 1910, yielding a mass estimate of 0.94 *M*☉ (which compares well with a more modern estimate of 1.00 *M*☉).
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Since hotter bodies radiate more energy than colder ones, a star's surface brightness can be estimated from its effective surface temperature, and star's spectrum gives its temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] If the star's distance is known, its absolute luminosity can also be estimated.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] From the absolute luminosity and distance, the star's surface area and its radius can be calculated.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Reasoning of this sort led to the realization, puzzling to astronomers at the time, that due to their relatively high temperature and relatively low absolute luminosity, Sirius B and 40 Eridani B must be very dense.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] When Ernst Öpik estimated the density of visual binary stars in 1916, he found that 40 Eridani B had a density of over 25000 times that of the Sun, which was so high that he called it "impossible".
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Such densities are possible because white dwarf material is not composed of atoms joined by chemical bonds, but rather consists of a plasma of unbound nuclei and electrons.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] There is therefore no obstacle to placing nuclei closer than normally allowed by electron orbitals limited by normal matter.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Eddington wondered what would happen when this plasma cooled and the energy to keep the atoms ionized was no longer sufficient.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Fowler in 1926 by an application of the newly devised quantum mechanics.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Since electrons obey the Pauli exclusion principle, no two electrons can occupy the same state, and they must obey Fermi–Dirac statistics, also introduced in 1926 to determine the statistical distribution of particles that satisfy the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] At zero temperature, therefore, electrons cannot all occupy the lowest-energy, or *ground*, state; some of them would have to occupy higher-energy states, forming a band of lowest-available energy states, the *Fermi sea*.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This state of the electrons, called *degenerate*, meant that a white dwarf could cool to zero temperature and still possess high energy.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The existence of a limiting mass that no white dwarf can exceed without collapsing to a neutron star is another consequence of being supported by electron degeneracy pressure.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Such limiting masses were calculated for cases of an idealized, constant density star in 1929 by Wilhelm Anderson and in 1930 by Edmund C.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This value was corrected by considering hydrostatic equilibrium for the density profile, and the presently known value of the limit was first published in 1931 by Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar in his paper "The Maximum Mass of Ideal White Dwarfs".
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] For a non-rotating white dwarf, it is equal to approximately 5.7 *M*☉ / *μ*e2, where *μ*e is the average molecular weight per electron of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] As the carbon-12 and oxygen-16 that predominantly compose a carbon–oxygen white dwarf both have atomic numbers equal to half their atomic weight, one should take *μ*e equal to 2 for such a star, leading to the commonly quoted value of 1.4 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The limiting mass is now called the *Chandrasekhar limit*.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Galactic models suggest the Milky Way galaxy currently contains about ten billion white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] There are currently thought to be eight white dwarfs among the one hundred star systems nearest the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The nearest and brightest known white dwarf is Sirius B, at 8.6 light years, the smaller component of the Sirius binary star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The population of white dwarf stars is expected to grow.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Existing stars with masses from about 0.07 to 10 *M*☉ include over 97% of the stars in the Milky Way and these stars will evolve into white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Although white dwarfs are known with estimated masses as low as 0.17 *M*☉ and as high as 1.33 *M*☉, the mass distribution is strongly peaked at 0.6 *M*☉, and the majority lie between 0.5 and 0.7 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The estimated radii of observed white dwarfs are typically 0.8–2% the radius of the Sun; this is comparable to the Earth's radius of approximately 0.9% solar radius.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A typical white dwarf has a density of between 104 and 107 g/cm3.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarfs are composed of one of the densest forms of matter known, surpassed only by other compact stars such as neutron stars and the hypothetical quark stars.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] At these densities the nuclei within the star are much closer than nuclei in ordinary matter.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Two nuclei in a white dwarf are separated by about 1.2×10−12 m, substantially less than a Bohr radius, 5.3×10−11 m, the rough size of a hydrogen atom.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The white dwarf matter is pressure ionized: there is no room for bound electron orbitals.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Rather than a hot thermal gas of atoms like the core of the Sun, the heat in the core of a white dwarf is associated with vibrating nuclei and the gas-like aspect providing pressure is due to the free electrons.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This unusual source of pressure is known as electron degeneracy pressure, a consequence of quantum mechanics.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The uncertainty principle requires the product of position uncertainty, $\Delta x$ , and momentum uncertainty, $\Delta p_{x}$ , to be larger than half of the reduced Planck constant: $\Delta x\times \Delta p_{x}>\hbar /2.$ If the position uncertainty is small, the momentum uncertainty must increase.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Furthermore, the Pauli principle of quantum mechanics requires every electron to be distinguishable, and that in turn means the uncertainty in the electron positions must be less than their average separation.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Forcing the electrons close together (smaller average separation) reduces their position uncertainty causing an increase in their momentum uncertainty.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] More uncertain momentum must also be higher momentum.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This increased momentum appears as a force that counteracts the gravitational force compressing the star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The balanced pressure at the center of a white dwarf will be on the order of 1.5 million times the pressure in the center of the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The central temperature will exceed 10 million K.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] While these conditions would fuse hydrogen the low luminosity of white dwarf stars implies the necessary nuclei are not present.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A typical white dwarf star, a **CO white dwarf**, is 99% carbon and oxygen by mass, with the remainder being a thin layer of He and H.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Main sequence stars close to the upper mass limit of 10 *M*☉ are thought to fuse carbon into neon, forming **O-Ne white dwarf** stars.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Very light stars, below 0.6 *M*☉ never fuse He into carbon and oxygen so they form **He-core white dwarfs**.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] It takes more time than the age of the universe for a light star to burn through its fuel, so any observed He-core white dwarfs are expected to result from mass loss to a companion in an interacting binary star system.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The current view is that this limit is not normally attained; increasing temperature and density inside the core ignite carbon fusion as the star approaches the limit (to within about 1%) before collapse is initiated.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] If a white dwarf star accumulates sufficient material from a stellar companion to raise its core temperature enough to ignite carbon fusion, it will undergo runaway nuclear fusion, completely disrupting it.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] where R is the radius, M is the mass of the white dwarf, and the subscript $\odot$ indicates the Sun; therefore ${R}/{R_{\odot }}$ is the radius in units of solar radius and ${M}/{M_{\odot }}$ is the mass in units of solar mass.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The chemical potential, $\mu _{e}$ is a thermodynamic property giving the change in energy as one electron is added or removed; it relates to the composition of the star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Numerical treatment of more complete models have been tested against observational data with good agreement.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Since this analysis uses the non-relativistic formula *p*2 / 2*m* for the kinetic energy, it is non-relativistic.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] When the electron velocity in a white dwarf is close to the speed of light, the kinetic energy formula approaches *pc* where *c* is the speed of light, and it can be shown that the Fermi gas model has no stable equilibrium in the ultrarelativistic limit.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The observation of many white dwarf stars implies that either they started with masses similar to the Sun or something dramatic happened to reduce their mass.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] For a more accurate computation of the mass-radius relationship and limiting mass of a white dwarf, one must compute the equation of state that describes the relationship between density and pressure in the white dwarf material.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] If the density and pressure are both set equal to functions of the radius from the center of the star, the system of equations consisting of the hydrostatic equation together with the equation of state can then be solved to find the structure of the white dwarf at equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In the non-relativistic case, the radius is inversely proportional to the cube root of the mass.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Relativistic corrections will alter the result so that the radius becomes zero at a finite value of the mass.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This is the limiting value of the mass—called the *Chandrasekhar limit*—at which the white dwarf can no longer be supported by electron degeneracy pressure.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The graph on the right shows the result of such a computation.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] It shows how radius varies with mass for non-relativistic (blue curve) and relativistic (green curve) models of a white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Both models treat the white dwarf as a cold Fermi gas in hydrostatic equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The average molecular weight per electron, *μ*e, has been set equal to 2.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Radius is measured in standard solar radii and mass in standard solar masses.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] These computations all assume that the white dwarf is non-rotating.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] If the white dwarf is rotating, the equation of hydrostatic equilibrium must be modified to take into account the centrifugal pseudo-force arising from working in a rotating frame.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] For a uniformly rotating white dwarf, the limiting mass increases only slightly.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] If the star is allowed to rotate nonuniformly, and viscosity is neglected, then, as was pointed out by Fred Hoyle in 1947, there is no limit to the mass for which it is possible for a model white dwarf to be in static equilibrium.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Not all of these model stars will be dynamically stable.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Rotating white dwarfs and the estimates of their diameter in terms of the angular velocity of rotation has been treated in the rigorous mathematical literature.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The fine structure of the free boundary of white dwarfs has also been analysed mathematically rigorously.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarfs have low luminosity and therefore occupy a strip at the bottom of the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, a graph of stellar luminosity versus color or temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] They should not be confused with low-luminosity objects at the low-mass end of the main sequence, such as the hydrogen-fusing red dwarfs, whose cores are supported in part by thermal pressure, or the even lower-temperature brown dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The visible radiation emitted by white dwarfs varies over a wide color range, from the whitish-blue color of an O-, B- or A-type main sequence star to the yellow-orange of a late K- or early M-type star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarf luminosity varies over 7 orders of magnitude, from over 100 times that of the Sun to under ⁠1/ 10000 ⁠ that of the Sun.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Assuming the Stefan–Boltzmann law, relating luminosity to the fourth power of the effective surface temperature, white dwarf effective surface temperatures extend from over 150000 K to barely under 4000 K.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Hot white dwarfs, with surface temperatures in excess of 30000 K, have been observed to be sources of soft (i.e., lower-energy) X-rays.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This enables the composition and structure of their atmospheres to be studied by soft X-ray and extreme ultraviolet observations.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarfs also radiate neutrinos through the Urca process.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This process has more effect on hotter and younger white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Because neutrinos can pass easily through stellar plasma, they can drain energy directly from the dwarf's interior; this mechanism is the dominant contribution to cooling for approximately the first 20 million years of a white dwarf's existence.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] As a result, the interior of the white dwarf maintains an almost uniform temperature as it cools down, starting at approximately 108 K shortly after the formation of the white dwarf and reaching less than 106 K for the coolest known white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] An outer shell of non-degenerate matter sits on top of the degenerate core.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The outermost layers, which are cooler than the interior, radiate roughly as a black body.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A white dwarf remains visible for a long time, as its tenuous outer atmosphere slowly radiates the thermal content of the degenerate interior.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] As was explained by Leon Mestel in 1952, unless the white dwarf accretes matter from a companion star or other source, its radiation comes from its stored heat, which is not replenished.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarfs have an extremely small surface area to radiate this heat from, so they cool gradually, remaining hot for a long time.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] As a white dwarf cools, its surface temperature decreases, the radiation that it emits reddens, and its luminosity decreases.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Since the white dwarf has no energy sink other than radiation, it follows that its cooling slows with time.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The rate of cooling has been estimated for a carbon white dwarf of 0.59 *M*☉ with a hydrogen atmosphere.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] After initially taking approximately 1.5 billion years to cool to a surface temperature of 7140 K, cooling approximately 500 more kelvins to 6590 K takes around 0.3 billion years, but the next two steps of around 500 kelvins (to 6030 K and 5550 K) take first 0.4 and then 1.1 billion years.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Most observed white dwarfs have relatively high surface temperatures, between 8000 K and 40000 K.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] However this is a selection effect: hotter, more luminous white dwarfs are easier to observe.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A white dwarf spends more of its lifetime at cooler temperatures: more cool white dwarfs than hot white dwarfs exist.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This trend stops at extremely cool white dwarfs; few white dwarfs are observed with surface temperatures below 4000 K, and one of the coolest so far observed, WD J2147–4035, has a surface temperature of approximately 3050 K.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The reason for this is that the Universe's age is finite; there has not been enough time for white dwarfs to cool below this temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The white dwarf luminosity function can therefore be used to find the time when stars started to form in a region; an estimate for the age of our galactic disk found in this way is 8 billion years.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A white dwarf will eventually, in many trillions of years, cool and become a non-radiating *black dwarf* in approximate thermal equilibrium with its surroundings and with the cosmic background radiation.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] No black dwarfs are thought to exist yet.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] At very low temperatures (<4000 K) white dwarfs with hydrogen in their atmosphere will be affected by collision induced absorption (CIA) of hydrogen molecules colliding with helium atoms.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This affects the optical red and infrared brightness of white dwarfs with a hydrogen or mixed hydrogen-helium atmosphere.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This makes old white dwarfs with this kind of atmosphere bluer than the main cooling sequence.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarfs with hydrogen-poor atmospheres, such as WD J2147–4035, are less affected by CIA and therefore have a yellow to orange color.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarf core material is a completely ionized plasma—a mixture of nuclei and electrons—that is initially in a fluid state.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] It was theoretically predicted in the 1960s that at a late stage of cooling, it should crystallize into a solid state, starting at its center.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The crystal structure is thought to be a body-centered cubic lattice.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In 1995 it was suggested that asteroseismological observations of pulsating white dwarfs yielded a potential test of the crystallization theory, and in 2004, observations were made that suggested approximately 90% of the mass of BPM 37093 had crystallized.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Other work gives a crystallized mass fraction of between 32% and 82%.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] As a white dwarf core undergoes crystallization into a solid phase, latent heat is released, which provides a source of thermal energy that delays its cooling.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Chemical fractionation between the ionic species in the plasma mixture can release a similar or even greater amount of energy.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This energy release was first confirmed in 2019 after the identification of a pile up in the cooling sequence of more than 15000 white dwarfs observed with the *Gaia* satellite.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Low-mass helium white dwarfs (mass < 0.20 *M*☉), often referred to as extremely low-mass white dwarfs (ELM WDs), are formed in binary systems.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] As a result of their hydrogen-rich envelopes, residual hydrogen burning via the CNO cycle may keep these white dwarfs hot for hundreds of millions of years.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In addition, they remain in a bloated proto-white dwarf stage for up to 2 Gyr before they reach the cooling track.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Although most white dwarfs are thought to be composed of carbon and oxygen, spectroscopy typically shows that their emitted light comes from an atmosphere that is observed to be either hydrogen or helium dominated.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The dominant element is usually at least 1000 times more abundant than all other elements.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] As explained by Schatzman in the 1940s, the high surface gravity is thought to cause this purity by gravitationally separating the atmosphere so that heavy elements are below and the lighter above.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This atmosphere, the only part of the white dwarf visible to us, is thought to be the top of an envelope that is a residue of the star's envelope in the AGB phase and may also contain material accreted from the interstellar medium.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The envelope is believed to consist of a helium-rich layer with mass no more than ⁠1/ 100 ⁠ of the star's total mass, which, if the atmosphere is hydrogen-dominated, is overlain by a hydrogen-rich layer with mass approximately ⁠1/ 10000 ⁠ of the star's total mass.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Although thin, these outer layers determine the thermal evolution of the white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The degenerate electrons in the bulk of a white dwarf conduct heat well.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Most of a white dwarf's mass is therefore at almost the same temperature (isothermal), and it is also hot: a white dwarf with surface temperature between 8000 K and 16000 K will have a core temperature between approximately 5000000 K and 20000000 K.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The white dwarf is kept from cooling very quickly only by its outer layers' opacity to radiation.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The first attempt to classify white dwarf spectra appears to have been by G.P.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Kuiper in 1941, and various classification schemes have been proposed and used since then.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The system currently in use was introduced by Edward M.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Greenstein and their coauthors in 1983 and has been subsequently revised several times.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] For example, a white dwarf with only He I lines in its spectrum and an effective temperature of 15000 K could be given the classification of "DB3", or, if warranted by the precision of the temperature measurement, "DB3.5".
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Likewise, a white dwarf with a polarized magnetic field, an effective temperature of 17000 K, and a spectrum dominated by He I lines that also had hydrogen features could be given the classification of DBAP3.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The symbols "?" and ":" may also be used if the correct classification is uncertain.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarfs whose primary spectral classification is DA have hydrogen-dominated atmospheres.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] They make up the majority, approximately 80%, of all observed white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The next class in number is of DBs, approximately 16%.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The hot, above 15000 K, DQ class (roughly 0.1%) have carbon-dominated atmospheres.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Those classified as DB, DC, DO, DZ, and cool DQ have helium-dominated atmospheres.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Assuming that carbon and metals are not present, which spectral classification is seen depends on the effective temperature.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Between approximately 100000 K to 45000 K, the spectrum will be classified DO, dominated by singly ionized helium.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] From 30000 K to 12000 K, the spectrum will be DB, showing neutral helium lines, and below about 12000 K, the spectrum will be featureless and classified DC.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Molecular hydrogen (H2) has been detected in spectra of the atmospheres of some white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] While theoretical work suggests that some types of white dwarfs may have stellar corona, searches at X-ray and radio wavelengths, where coronae are most easily detected, have been unsuccessful.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A few white dwarfs have been observed to have inhomogeneous atmosphere with one side dominated by hydrogen and the other side dominated by helium.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Around 25–33% of white dwarfs have metal lines in their spectra, which is notable because any heavy elements in a white dwarf should sink into the star's interior in just a small fraction of the star's lifetime.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The prevailing explanation for metal-rich white dwarfs is that they have recently accreted rocky planetesimals.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The bulk composition of the accreted object can be measured from the strengths of the metal lines.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] For example, a 2015 study of the white dwarf Ton 345 concluded that its metal abundances were consistent with those of a differentiated, rocky planet whose mantle had been eroded by the host star's wind during its asymptotic giant branch phase.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Magnetic fields in white dwarfs with a strength at the surface of c.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] 1 million gauss (100 teslas) were predicted by P.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Blackett in 1947 as a consequence of a physical law he had proposed, which stated that an uncharged, rotating body should generate a magnetic field proportional to its angular momentum.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] This putative law, sometimes called the *Blackett effect*, was never generally accepted, and by the 1950s even Blackett felt it had been refuted.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] In the 1960s, it was proposed that white dwarfs might have magnetic fields due to conservation of total surface magnetic flux that existed in its progenitor star phase.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] 100 gauss (0.01 T) in the progenitor star would thus become a surface magnetic field of c.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] 100 × 1002 = 1 million gauss (100 T) once the star's radius had shrunk by a factor of 100.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The first magnetic white dwarf to be discovered was GJ 742 (also known as GRW +70 8247), which was identified by James Kemp, John Swedlund, John Landstreet and Roger Angel in 1970 to host a magnetic field by its emission of circularly polarized light.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] It is thought to have a surface field of approximately 300 million gauss (30 kT).
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Since 1970, magnetic fields have been discovered in well over 200 white dwarfs, ranging from 2×103 to 109 gauss (0.2 T to 100 kT).
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Many of the presently known magnetic white dwarfs are identified by low-resolution spectroscopy, which is able to reveal the presence of a magnetic field of 1 megagauss or more.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Thus the basic identification process also sometimes results in discovery of magnetic fields.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarf magnetic fields may also be measured without spectral lines, using the techniques of broadband circular polarimetry, or maybe through measurement of their frequencies of radio emission via the electron cyclotron maser.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] It has been estimated that at least 10% of white dwarfs have fields in excess of 1 million gauss (100 T).
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The magnetic fields in a white dwarf may allow for the existence of a new type of chemical bond, perpendicular paramagnetic bonding, in addition to ionic and covalent bonds, though detecting molecules bonded in this way is expected to be difficult.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The highly magnetized white dwarf in the binary system AR Scorpii was identified in 2016 as the first pulsar in which the compact object is a white dwarf instead of a neutron star.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A second white dwarf pulsar was discovered in 2023.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Early calculations suggested that there might be white dwarfs whose luminosity varied with a period of around 10 seconds, but searches in the 1960s failed to observe this.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The first variable white dwarf found was HL Tau 76; in 1965 and 1966, and was observed to vary with a period of approximately 12.5 minutes.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The reason for this period being longer than predicted is that the variability of HL Tau 76, like that of the other pulsating variable white dwarfs known, arises from non-radial gravity wave pulsations.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] GW Vir stars are not, strictly speaking, white dwarfs, but are stars that are in a position on the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram between the asymptotic giant branch and the white dwarf region.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] These variables all exhibit small (1%–30%) variations in light output, arising from a superposition of vibrational modes with periods of hundreds to thousands of seconds.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Observation of these variations gives asteroseismological evidence about the interiors of white dwarfs.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Alternate fusing of the helium shell and hydrogen shells creates thermal pulses; these pulses combine with convective currents to create dust grains that are driven outward by radiation pressure creating strong stellar winds.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The ejected mass forms a planetary nebula leaving behind a core, which is the remnant white dwarf.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] A white dwarf radiates light from residual heat, not from nuclear fusion.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] White dwarf stars with less than 25% of a solar mass are all found in binary star systems.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] The proportion of white dwarfs in binary systems declines to 34% for masses in the range 0.5–0.75 *M*☉.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] It is thought that, over a lifespan that considerably exceeds the age of the universe (c.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] 13.8 billion years), such a star will eventually burn all its hydrogen, for a while becoming a blue dwarf, and end its evolution as a helium white dwarf composed chiefly of helium-4 nuclei.
[src:stellar-physics/white-dwarf-p01] Due to the very long time this process takes, it is not thought to be the origin of the observed helium white dwarfs.
